Further research would be required to establish such connections.\n\nRunning tool: astrokb\n\n{\n  \"query\": \"What key experimental studies have demonstrated synthesis of threonine or its precursors under simulated prebiotic conditions?\",\n  \"searchType\": 0\n}\n### Key Experimental Studies on the Synthesis of Threonine or Its Precursors\n\nSeveral experimental studies have explored the synthesis of amino acids, including threonine or its precursors, under simulated prebiotic conditions. These studies provide insights into the chemical pathways that may have contributed to the emergence of life on Earth. Below is a synthesis of the most relevant findings:\n\n---\n\n#### Formaldehyde and Ammonia as Precursors\nThe study by Y. Wolman, S. L. Miller, J. Ibanez, and J. Or\u00f3 in 1971 demonstrated that formaldehyde and ammonia can act as precursors to prebiotic amino acids, potentially including threonine, under simulated prebiotic conditions. This research highlights the role of simple molecules in amino acid synthesis during early Earth conditions [Data: Sources (23270)].\n\n---\n\n#### General Prebiotic Chemistry Experiments\nExperimental studies in prebiotic chemistry, such as spark discharge experiments pioneered by Miller and Urey, reductive aminations, aqueous Strecker-type reactions, and Fischer-Tropsch type syntheses, have successfully produced amino acids under plausibly prebiotic conditions. However, these experiments generally yield racemic mixtures of L- and D-enantiomers, and there is no direct evidence specifically for the synthesis of threonine or its precursors in these studies [Data: Sources (15225)].\n\n---\n\n#### Strecker Reaction Pathway\nThe Strecker reaction, involving aldehydes, is identified as a key pathway for the prebiotic synthesis of \u03b1-amino acids, which may include threonine or its precursors. This reaction is considered a plausible mechanism for amino acid formation in early Earth environments. However, the study also notes that