 to the prebiotic synthesis of threonine?\",\n  \"searchType\": 0\n}\nThe dataset does not provide evidence that greigite, pyrite, or montmorillonite specifically act as catalysts in reactions relevant to the prebiotic synthesis of threonine. However, magnetite has been highlighted as a mineral catalyst with significant relevance to prebiotic chemistry, although its role in the synthesis of threonine is not explicitly mentioned.\n\n### Magnetite's Role in Prebiotic Chemistry\nMagnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) is known to facilitate reactions central to the prebiotic synthesis of organic compounds. It forms at relatively low temperatures (~360 K) and plays a catalytic role in Fischer-Tropsch-Type (FTT) reactions, which are important for generating primordial organic compounds [Data: Sources (19309, 19315)]. The Cold Bokkeveld carbonaceous chondrite, which contains magnetite, has also been shown to catalyze FTT reactions, further supporting its catalytic activity in prebiotic contexts [Data: Sources (19315)].\n\n### Montmorillonite and Other Clays\nMontmorillonite and other clays, such as layered double hydroxides, are recognized for their ability to promote processes like the ligation of activated nucleotides and amino acids, as well as the self-assembly of vesicles as protocell models. These clays act as adsorption templates for monomers, facilitating bond formation under appropriate energy conditions. However, their role in the synthesis of threonine specifically is not mentioned in the dataset [Data: Sources (9431)].\n\n### Sulfide and Other Minerals\nThe dataset notes that carbonaceous chondrites contain spatially separated sulfide, magnetite, metal, and phyllosilicate grains, which allow for catalytic activity without inhibition from sulfide grains. While this supports the general catalytic potential of these minerals in prebiotic reactions, no direct link to threonine synthesis is provided [Data: Sources (19315)].\n\n### Conclusion\nAmong the minerals mentioned, magnetite is the only one explicitly identified as a catalyst in prebiotic chemical reactions, particularly through its role in FTT synthesis. However, the dataset does not provide evidence for its involvement\u2014or that of greigite, pyrite, or montmorillonite\u2014in the specific synthesis of threonine. Further research would be required to establish such connections.\n\nRunning tool: astrokb\n\n{\n  \"query\": \"What key experimental studies have demonstrated synthesis of threonine or its precursors under simulated prebiotic conditions?\",\n  \"searchType\": 0\n}\n### Key Experimental Studies on the Synthesis of Threonine or Its Precursors\n\nSeveral experimental studies have explored the synthesis of amino acids, including threonine or its precursors, under simulated prebiotic conditions. These studies provide insights into the chemical pathways that may have contributed to the emergence of life on Earth. Below is a synthesis of the most relevant findings:\n\n---\n\n#### Formaldehyde and Ammonia as Precursors\nThe study by Y. Wolman, S. L. Miller, J. Ibanez, and J. Or\u00f3 in 1971 demonstrated that formaldehyde and ammonia can act as precursors to prebiotic amino acids, potentially including threonine, under simulated prebiotic conditions. This research highlights the role of simple molecules in amino acid synthesis during early Earth conditions [Data: Sources (23270)].\n\n---\n\n#### General Prebiotic Chemistry Experiments\nExperimental studies in prebiotic chemistry, such as spark discharge experiments pioneered by Miller and Urey, reductive aminations, aqueous Strecker-type reactions, and Fischer-Tropsch type syntheses, have successfully produced amino acids under plausibly prebiotic conditions. However, these experiments generally yield racemic mixtures of L- and D-enantiomers, and there is no direct evidence specifically for the synthesis of threonine or its precursors in these studies [Data: Sources (15225)].\n\n---\n\n#### Strecker Reaction Pathway\nThe Strecker reaction, involving aldehydes, is identified as a key pathway for the prebiotic synthesis of \u03b1-amino acids, which may include threonine or its precursors. This reaction is considered a plausible mechanism for amino acid formation in early Earth environments. However, the study also notes that modern biological systems synthesize amino acids through transamination of \u03b1-keto acids, suggesting an evolutionary transition from prebiotic chemistry to biological pathways [Data: Sources (6940)].\n\n---\n\n#### Thioester Chemistry and Protometabolic Pathways\nResearch into thioester chemistry has demonstrated its coupling with core metabolites, resembling biochemical processes. This pathway may have facilitated the synthesis of amino acids, including threonine or its precursors, under prebiotic conditions. The study describes a network originating at glyoxylate and pyruvate, which integrates prebiotically relevant inputs and connects intermediates such as succinyl, malonyl, and acetyl thioesters to critical TCA cycle molecules like \u03b1-ketoglutarate, fumarate, and malate [Data: Sources (995)].\n\n---\n\n#### Extraterrestrial Contributions\nY. Oba et al. in 2020 identified extraterrestrial hexamethylenetetramine in meteorites, which is considered a precursor in prebiotic chemistry within the inner solar system. This compound may have contributed to the synthesis of amino acids, including threonine, through extraterrestrial delivery to early Earth [Data: Sources (23270)].\n\n---\n\n### Limitations and Challenges\nWhile these studies provide valuable insights, direct evidence of prebiotic chiral selection or the specific synthesis of threonine under prebiotic conditions remains elusive. Geological and biological processes over billions of years may have overwritten any such records, limiting our ability to confirm the exact pathways for threonine synthesis [Data: Sources (15225)].\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion\nThe synthesis of threonine or its precursors under simulated prebiotic conditions has been explored through various experimental approaches, including formaldehyde-ammonia reactions, Strecker-type chemistry, thioester-mediated pathways, and extraterrestrial contributions. However, direct evidence specific to threonine remains limited, and further research is needed to clarify its prebiotic origins.\n\nRunning tool: astrokb\n\n{\n  \"query\": \"Which prebiotic environments (e.g., alkaline hydrothermal vents, volcanic hot springs, tidal flats) are most relevant for the synthesis of threonine?\",\n  \"searchType\": 0\n}\n### Prebiotic Environments Relevant for Threonine Synthesis\n\nThe synthesis of threonine, an amino acid potentially significant in prebiotic chemistry, is influenced by the geochemical and physical conditions of various environments. Among the prebiotic settings studied, submarine hydrothermal systems (SHSs), particularly alkaline hydrothermal vents, emerge as highly relevant due to their unique characteristics. Below is a detailed exploration of these environments and their suitability for threonine synthesis.\n\n---\n\n#### **Submarine Hydrothermal Systems (SHSs)**\nSubmarine hydrothermal systems are considered promising environments for the abiotic synthesis of amino acids, including threonine. These systems provide high concentrations of key precursors such as ammonia (NH\u2083), hydrogen cyanide (HCN), and formaldehyde (H\u2082CO), which are essential for amino acid synthesis through pathways like the Strecker synthesis. However, the effectiveness of SHSs for threonine synthesis depends on specific geochemical conditions, such as the presence of reducing environments and sufficient reactant concentrations [Data: Sources (15641)].\n\n##### **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**\nAlkaline hydrothermal vents, particularly those associated with serpentinization processes, are highlighted as ideal environments for early chemical evolution. These vents are characterized by alkaline and hydrogen-rich conditions, which are conducive to prebiotic reactions. Serpentine-hosted systems, such as the Lost City hydrothermal field, are proposed as favorable settings due to their lower temperature regimes and dynamic circulation of reactants and products. These features may enhance the synthesis of threonine and other organic molecules [Data: Sources (15866, 2626, 2627)].\n\n##### **Temperature Considerations**\nLower-temperature hydrothermal systems, with temperatures around 100\u00b0C, are more favorable for organic synthesis compared to high-temperature systems. High temperatures tend to degrade amino acids, including threonine, leading to extremely low equilibrium concentrations. Environments like low-temperature seeps and \"beehive\" hydrothermal vent systems are therefore considered more viable for amino acid synthesis [Data: Sources (2626, 2627, 2629)].\n\n---\n\n#### **Laboratory Simulations and Experimental Insights**\nLaboratory simulations of hydrothermal systems have demonstrated the synthesis of amino acids under high-temperature and high-pressure conditions. While yields are typically low due to rapid degradation and short experimental durations, these studies suggest that SHSs might have supported threonine synthesis under specific conditions. Experimental approaches continue to provide valuable insights into the role of hydrothermal systems in prebiotic chemistry [Data: Sources (2546, 2655)].\n\n---\n\n#### **Challenges in Detection**\nDespite the theoretical plausibility of threonine synthesis in hydrothermal systems, the detection of abiogenic amino acids in vent fluids remains elusive. This is likely due to rapid degradation of intermediates at high temperatures or synthesis occurring at levels below analytical sensitivity. These challenges underscore the need for further research to confirm the role of hydrothermal systems in amino acid formation [Data: Sources (2629)].\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion\nAmong prebiotic environments, alkaline hydrothermal vents stand out as the most relevant for threonine synthesis due to their favorable geochemical conditions, moderate temperatures, and dynamic circulation of reactants. Lower-temperature submarine hydrothermal systems, such as those found in the Lost City hydrothermal field, are particularly promising. However, challenges in detection and experimental limitations highlight the need for continued exploration of these environments to fully understand their role in prebiotic chemistry.\n\nRunning tool: astrokb\n\n{\n  \"query\": \"What are the main unresolved challenges or debates in the literature regarding the prebiotic synthesis of threonine?\",\n  \"searchType\": 0\n}\n### Unresolved Challenges in the Prebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of threonine, like other amino acids, remains a complex and debated topic in the field of origins-of-life research. Several unresolved challenges and debates in the literature highlight the difficulties in understanding how threonine could have emerged under prebiotic conditions. These challenges span chemical plausibility, environmental constraints, and evolutionary transitions. Below is a synthesis of the key issues:\n\n---\n\n#### **Chemical Pathways and Plausibility**\nOne of the central debates revolves around the plausibility of proposed chemical pathways for amino acid synthesis, including threonine. While organic chemistry provides numerous pathways for amino acid synthesis under conditions that might have existed on early Earth, the specific selection of the 20-or-so proteinogenic alpha-amino acids, including threonine, remains unclear. This selection is particularly puzzling in the context of their ease of synthesis from a protometabolism similar to core carbon metabolism [Data: Sources (1012)]. \n\nAdditionally, the compatibility of amine and hydrazine with electrophilic functional groups such as thioesters and acyl phosphates poses a challenge. These functional groups are critical in protometabolism, but their interactions under prebiotic conditions are not well understood, raising questions about their role in amino acid synthesis [Data: Sources (1012)].\n\n---\n\n#### **Environmental Constraints**\nThe geochemical conditions of early Earth play a critical role in determining the feasibility of threonine synthesis. Hydrothermal systems, often proposed as sites for prebiotic chemistry, are thought to provide suitable environments for amino acid formation. However, the specific conditions required for threonine synthesis remain uncertain, and recreating these environments in laboratory settings has proven difficult [Data: Sources (2547, 512)].\n\nAnother challenge is reconciling \"clean chemistry\" approaches with the \"prebiotic clutter\" of early Earth environments. The messy chemistries of primordial Earth, with numerous interfering reactions, could hinder the chemical evolution necessary for amino acid synthesis. This issue complicates efforts to model realistic prebiotic scenarios [Data: Sources (12547)].\n\n---\n\n#### **Energy Conservation and Activation**\nA significant unresolved issue in prebiotic chemistry is the lack of experimental evidence linking thioester chemistry and phosphate chemistry in the context of energy conservation. Efficient and reversible interconversion of thioesters and acyl phosphates, which are key aspects of bioenergetics, has not been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions. This gap is particularly relevant to the synthesis of threonine, as these activated acyl species are thought to play a role in amino acid formation [Data: Sources (979)].\n\nMoreover, simple thioesters tend to hydrolyze faster than they undergo useful intermolecular reactions, which may further hinder their role in prebiotic synthesis pathways [Data: Sources (979)].\n\n---\n\n#### **Evolutionary Transitions**\nUnderstanding the evolutionary switch between prebiotic and biotic chemistries is another major challenge. Extant biochemistry primarily utilizes \u03b1-ketoacids as building blocks via transamination, but prebiotic models do not clearly explain how this transition occurred. This gap in understanding complicates efforts to reconstruct plausible pathways for threonine synthesis [Data: Sources (6943)].\n\nAdditionally, the use of ammonia rather than bifunctional amines in biochemistry remains unexplained. This broader unresolved issue may impact our understanding of why specific amino acids, including threonine, were selected during prebiotic evolution [Data: Sources (1012)].\n\n---\n\n#### **Experimental Limitations**\nExperimental setups for studying abiotic synthesis often face criticism for lacking prebiotic realism. Issues such as unrealistic concentrations, spatial-sequence separation, and the use of pure starting materials limit the applicability of these experiments to early Earth conditions. These limitations hinder progress in understanding the synthesis of threonine and other amino acids [Data: Sources (12546)].\n\nAutotrophic approaches, which aim to reproduce biological pathways from the very beginning, also face inadequate experimental support. This limitation further complicates efforts to address the prebiotic synthesis of threonine [Data: Sources (6943)].\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion\nThe prebiotic synthesis of threonine is hindered by unresolved challenges related to chemical plausibility, environmental constraints, energy conservation, evolutionary transitions, and experimental limitations. These issues highlight the complexity of reconstructing realistic prebiotic scenarios and underscore the need for further interdisciplinary research to bridge gaps in our understanding of life's origins.\n\n### Comprehensive Report: Prebiotic Synthesis of Threonine\n\n#### **Phase 1: Structural Decomposition**\nThreonine is a hydroxy-amino acid with the following features:\n- **Functional Groups**:\n  - Amino group (-NH2)\n  - Hydroxyl group (-OH)\n  - Carboxyl group (-COOH)\n- **Carbon Backbone**:\n  - C4 backbone: CH3-CH(OH)-CH(NH2)-COOH\n- **Immediate Precursors**:\n  - Likely precursors include glycine (C2 amino acid), acetaldehyde (C2 aldehyde), and \u03b1-keto acids such as pyruvate.\n- **Named Synthetic Frameworks**:\n  - Relevant frameworks include Strecker synthesis, phosphoro-Strecker synthesis, and thioester-mediated pathways.\n\n---\n\n### **1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes**\nSeveral pathways have been proposed for threonine synthesis under prebiotic conditions:\n1. **Strecker Reaction**: Reaction of aldehydes, cyanide, and ammonia to form \u03b1-aminonitriles, which hydrolyze to amino acids.\n2. **Phosphoro-Strecker Synthesis**: Involves aldehydes, diamidophosphate (DAP), and HCN, forming intermediates like N-phosphoroaminonitriles.\n3. **Abiotic Conversion of \u03b1-Ketoacids**: Transamination of \u03b1-ketoacids (e.g., pyruvate) with ammonia.\n4. **Hydrothermal Systems**: High-temperature and pressure environments conducive to amino acid synthesis.\n5. **Surface/UV Chemistry**: Reactions on mineral surfaces or under UV light.\n6. **Dry-Wet Cycles**: Alternating solid-state polymerization and aqueous solution phases.\n7. **Cyanosulfidic Chemistry**: Polymerization of glycolonitrile and bisulfite adducts.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Key Intermediates and Precursors**\nImportant intermediates and precursors include:\n- **Smaller Precursors**:\n  - Keto acids (e.g., pyruvate, glyoxylate)\n  - Aldehydes (e.g., formaldehyde, acetaldehyde)\n  - Hydrogen cyanide (HCN)\n  - Ammonia (NH3)\n- **Chemical Intermediates**:\n  - N-phosphoroaminonitriles (phosphoro-Strecker synthesis)\n  - Thioesters (e.g., succinyl, malonyl, acetyl thioesters)\n  - Imine-like intermediates\n  - Hydroxymethane sulfonate\n\n---\n\n### **3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions**\n- **Phosphoro-Strecker Synthesis**:\n  - pH-dependent steps (neutral, alkaline, acidic).\n  - Involves aldehydes, DAP, HCN, and hydrogen sulfide.\n- **Hydrothermal Systems**:\n  - High temperatures (~100\u00b0C) and pressures.\n  - Thermal degradation limits amino acid stability.\n- **Surface/UV Chemistry**:\n  - Catalysis on mineral surfaces under UV light.\n- **Challenges**:\n  - Lack of specific yield/selectivity data for threonine.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces**\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**:\n  - Facilitates Fischer-Tropsch-Type (FTT) reactions for organic synthesis.\n- **Montmorillonite**:\n  - Promotes ligation of nucleotides and amino acids.\n- **Sulfide Minerals**:\n  - Catalytic activity in carbonaceous chondrites.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Experimental Evidence**\nKey studies include:\n- **Formaldehyde-Ammonia Reactions**: Demonstrated amino acid synthesis under simulated prebiotic conditions.\n- **Strecker Reaction**: Plausible pathway for \u03b1-amino acid formation.\n- **Thioester Chemistry**: Coupling with core metabolites resembling biochemical processes.\n- **Extraterrestrial Contributions**: Hexamethylenetetramine in meteorites as a precursor.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Environmental Context**\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**:\n  - Moderate temperatures (~100\u00b0C) and dynamic reactant circulation.\n  - Lost City hydrothermal field as a promising site.\n- **Lower-Temperature Systems**:\n  - Favorable for organic synthesis compared to high-temperature systems.\n- **Challenges**:\n  - Rapid degradation of intermediates at high temperatures.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Open Questions and Challenges**\n1. **Chemical Pathways**:\n   - Plausibility of threonine synthesis from protometabolic cycles.\n   - Compatibility of functional groups under prebiotic conditions.\n2. **Environmental Constraints**:\n   - Difficulty in recreating realistic prebiotic environments.\n   - \"Prebiotic clutter\" interfering with clean chemistry.\n3. **Energy Conservation**:\n   - Lack of experimental evidence linking thioester and phosphate chemistry.\n4. **Evolutionary Transitions**:\n   - Unclear switch from prebiotic to biotic chemistries.\n5. **Experimental Limitations**:\n   - Unrealistic concentrations and pure starting materials in laboratory setups.\n\n---\n\n### **Phase 2: Targeted Drill-Down Queries**\nTo address gaps and sparse data:\n1. Investigate Strecker synthesis on C2 aldehydes for threonine precursors.\n2. Explore thioester-mediated pathways for C4 amino acids.\n3. Query for magnetite-catalyzed reactions involving threonine precursors.\n4. Search for glyoxylate and pyruvate-based synthesis networks.\n5. Examine experimental setups for amino acid synthesis in hydrothermal systems.\n\n---\n\n### **Phase 3: Verification and Cross-Referencing**\n1. **Carbon Atom Trace**:\n   - C1 (formaldehyde) + C1 (HCN) \u2192 C2 (glycine) \u2192 C4 (threonine).\n2. **Reaction Validation**:\n   - Verify Strecker synthesis and transamination pathways.\n3. **Environmental Coherence**:\n   - Assess compatibility of hydrothermal and surface reactions.\n\n---\n\n### **Conclusion**\nThe prebiotic synthesis of threonine likely involved multiple pathways, including Strecker synthesis, phosphoro-Strecker synthesis, and thioester-mediated reactions. Alkaline hydrothermal vents are the most promising environments, but unresolved challenges in chemical plausibility, environmental constraints, and experimental limitations highlight the need for further research. This report synthesizes current knowledge and identifies key areas for future investigation.\n=== END KNOWLEDGE BASE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid, C4H9NO3) is synthesized via a multi-environment prebiotic network. The strategy begins with hydrothermal CO2 reduction to C1 units (formate, formaldehyde, CO) and C3 units (pyruvate) on iron-sulfur minerals. These feed into surface aldol, formose, and Strecker chemistry to build the C4 backbone and install the amino and hydroxyl groups. Two major convergence hubs are lactaldehyde (the Strecker aldehyde precursor) and 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate (the reductive amination precursor). Ten distinct pathways span hydrothermal carbon fixation, Fischer-Tropsch synthesis, formose sugar chemistry, Strecker synthesis, phosphoro-Strecker synthesis, cyanosulfidic chemistry, reductive amination of alpha-keto acids, glyoxylate aldol pathways, decarboxylation-aldol sequences, and wet-dry peptide assembly. Hub molecules (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, HCN, lactaldehyde) interconnect across all three environments.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCOOH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methylglyoxal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h3H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropionaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2NO3P(NH2)2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"diamidophosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAP\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on greigite surface Fe-Ni-S clusters, analogous to biological [Fe4S4] cofactors. H2 dissociatively adsorbs, and surface hydride transfers to CO2, yielding formate via a surface-bound formate intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is well established as a prebiotic carbon fixation pathway at alkaline hydrothermal vents, analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway in acetogens. Greigite is structurally similar to biological iron-sulfur clusters (Preiner et al., 2020; Yamaguchi et al., 2014). The Lost City hydrothermal field provides H2-rich, alkaline conditions favorable for this reaction (Sources 15866, 2626).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on mackinawite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing conditions, subseafloor hydrothermal circulation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced via surface hydride on mackinawite FeS layers. The carboxylate oxygen is activated on the mineral surface, and a two-electron reduction yields formaldehyde and water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Sequential reduction of CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde on iron-sulfur minerals follows the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway analogy. Mackinawite is a precursor to greigite and provides layered FeS surfaces for further reduction steps (Roldan et al., 2015). Formaldehyde is a critical C1 building block for prebiotic chemistry (Sources 15634, 6942).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions, CO/H2 gas phase on magnetite surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs on magnetite surface, undergoes stepwise hydrogenation via dissociated H2 to form surface methyl and methylene species. Chain growth produces C2 oxygenates (acetaldehyde) alongside C1 oxygenates (formaldehyde).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite catalyzes FTT reactions producing aldehydes, alcohols, and hydrocarbons from CO + H2. Magnetite forms at ~360K and is catalytically active for FTT synthesis (Sources 19309, 19315). The Cold Bokkeveld chondrite containing magnetite catalyzes FTT reactions. Acetaldehyde is a key C2 building block for threonine synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 fixation to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite mixed mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, multi-step CO2 fixation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO \u2192 acetyl intermediate \u2192 pyruvate. Greigite mediates the initial reduction steps while magnetite supports C-C coupling. Pyruvate forms via carboxylation of an acetyl-mineral intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on iron-sulfur/iron-oxide mineral assemblages has been demonstrated as a prebiotic analog of the acetyl-CoA pathway. Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub connecting carbon fixation to amino acid synthesis (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2017). Sources (995, 9332, 9334) identify pyruvate as a prebiotically relevant hub molecule.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal decarboxylation, mildly acidic hydrothermal fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation on the pyrite surface. The C2-C3 bond cleaves heterolytically, releasing CO2 and producing acetaldehyde. Pyrite surface stabilizes the transition state via Lewis acid interactions with the keto carbonyl.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of alpha-keto acids is a well-known prebiotic reaction, producing aldehydes that serve as Strecker synthesis substrates. This provides a second convergent route to acetaldehyde from pyruvate (Sources 6940, 995). Pyrite surfaces catalyze such decarboxylation reactions at hydrothermal temperatures.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to glyoxylate on elemental iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strongly reducing conditions, native iron surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe0 provides electrons for CO2 reduction. Two CO2 molecules are sequentially reduced and coupled on the Fe0 surface to yield glyoxylate (OHCCOOH), the simplest alpha-keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is identified as a prebiotically relevant input alongside pyruvate (Sources 995, 9332, 9334). Fe0 is a strong reductant for CO2 fixation and has been shown to drive reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids (Sources 1026). Glyoxylate formation from CO2 on metallic iron provides the C2 keto-acid needed for aldol routes to threonine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals with Ca(OH)2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline evaporitic pool, formose reaction conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. Ca(OH)2 provides alkalinity; borate minerals stabilize the glycolaldehyde product by forming borate esters, preventing further uncontrolled oligomerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction is a canonical prebiotic pathway for sugar synthesis from formaldehyde. Borate minerals stabilize glycolaldehyde and other sugars, channeling the reaction toward biologically relevant products (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012). This is the entry point for the formose-to-lactaldehyde pathway to threonine (Sources 15634).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface with borate stabilization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde enolizes on the montmorillonite surface; the enolate attacks the formaldehyde carbonyl in a crossed aldol reaction, yielding glyceraldehyde. Borate complexation stabilizes the triose product against retro-aldol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde is a key step in the formose reaction network. Montmorillonite catalyzes such condensations (Sources 9431). Glyceraldehyde is a critical C3 intermediate en route to methylglyoxal and then lactaldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Dehydration of glyceraldehyde to methylglyoxal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalyst under UV\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, no ozone shield, shallow pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes UV-assisted dehydration on TiO2 surface. The C2-OH is eliminated as water, generating the alpha-dicarbonyl methylglyoxal (pyruvaldehyde). TiO2 surface generates radical intermediates that facilitate the elimination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Methylglyoxal is a known product of glyceraldehyde dehydration and a formose reaction intermediate. UV photocatalysis on TiO2 drives dehydration reactions under early Earth surface conditions with strong UV radiation and no ozone layer (Sources 21187). Methylglyoxal is a direct precursor to lactaldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on sulfide minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"stibnite and other sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly reducing surface pool, H2S as reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Methylglyoxal (CH3COCHO) is selectively reduced at the more electrophilic keto carbonyl. H2S donates electrons via the sulfide mineral surface, reducing the C2 keto group to a hydroxyl, yielding lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO) while preserving the aldehyde function.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Selective reduction of alpha-dicarbonyls is facilitated by sulfide minerals acting as electron mediators. H2S provides reducing equivalents in cyanosulfidic chemistry (Sources 9381, 9382, 10209). The selective reduction of one carbonyl over another on mineral surfaces is analogous to enzymatic selectivity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH3 to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface concentrates reactants\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ambient evaporitic pool, pH 7-9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. HCN then undergoes nucleophilic addition to the imine C=N bond, yielding the alpha-aminonitrile (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile). Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants and stabilizes the imine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker reaction is the most widely studied prebiotic pathway for amino acid synthesis (Sources 6940, 6942, 985). Lactaldehyde is the appropriate aldehyde for threonine formation. Imine-like intermediates are short-lived under aqueous conditions but are driven to completion (Sources 1026). Montmorillonite clays concentrate and catalyze such reactions (Sources 9431).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis, mildly acidic to neutral pH, wet-dry cycling may concentrate products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-CN) of the aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to an amide (-CONH2), then to a carboxylic acid (-COOH), releasing ammonia. This yields threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the terminal step of the Strecker synthesis and occurs readily in aqueous solution at moderate temperatures and neutral to mildly acidic pH (Wolman et al., 1971; Sources 6940, 23270). This completes the Strecker route to threonine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glyoxylate and acetaldehyde to 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 6-8, phosphate-buffered evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde enolizes in the slightly alkaline phosphate-buffered environment. The enolate attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of glyoxylate in a crossed aldol condensation, forming the C4 alpha-keto-beta-hydroxy acid (2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate), the alpha-keto acid corresponding to threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate and pyruvate are identified as prebiotically relevant inputs in protometabolic networks (Sources 995, 9332, 9334). Aldol condensation of alpha-keto acids with aldehydes produces higher alpha-keto acids that serve as reductive amination substrates. This mirrors the biological connection between TCA cycle intermediates and amino acid biosynthesis (Sources 6987, 6944).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine on Fe0\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH < 7, imine-like intermediate formed transiently\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH3 attacks the keto carbonyl of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate, forming a transient imine (Schiff base). Fe0 provides reducing equivalents to reduce the C=N bond to C-NH2, completing the reductive amination to threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids by NH3 on Fe0 under aqueous conditions (pH < 7) is a demonstrated prebiotic pathway for amino acid synthesis (Sources 1026). Fe0 serves as both reductant and surface catalyst. This mimics biological transamination and represents the alpha-keto acid route to threonine (Sources 6940, 6943, 6987).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + DAP + HCN to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate mineral surface, pH 7\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH, DAP as phosphorylating/activating agent\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with DAP to form an N-phosphoroamino intermediate, which then reacts with HCN to yield N-phosphoroaminonitrile. Under acidic conditions (pH 1.5), the phosphoro group is lost yielding the free aminonitrile. The pathway selectively targets aldehydes over ketones, avoiding unnatural alpha,alpha-disubstituted amino acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The phosphoro-Strecker synthesis is a prebiotically plausible variation of the Strecker reaction that uses diamidophosphate (DAP) as an activating agent (Sources 21192, 21193). This pathway operates at neutral pH and selectively produces aminonitriles from aldehydes, providing a second convergent route to the threonine aminonitrile intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde to threonine precursor via cyanosulfidic intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite, MoS2)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals + UV on TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic conditions, H2S/HCN co-present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"In the cyanosulfidic scenario, acetaldehyde reacts with HCN to form cyanohydrin (lactonitrile). Under UV irradiation, H2S-mediated reduction generates the hydroxylated aldehyde (lactaldehyde) via a series of radical and sulfide-mediated transformations. This provides an alternative pathway from acetaldehyde to the key Strecker aldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The cyanosulfidic scenario (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland and co-workers) provides UV-driven pathways from simple feedstocks (HCN, H2S, aldehydes) to amino acid precursors (Sources 9381, 9382, 9376, 16400). This represents an alternative surface route to lactaldehyde, complementing the formose-based pathway.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 \u2192 Formate \u2192 Formaldehyde \u2192 Formose \u2192 Strecker Route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate at hydrothermal vents on greigite, then further reduced to formaldehyde on mackinawite. Formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where formose chemistry builds glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde. Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3 on lactaldehyde produces the aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch Acetaldehyde \u2192 Cyanosulfidic \u2192 Strecker Route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO and H2 undergo FTT synthesis on magnetite to yield acetaldehyde and formaldehyde. Acetaldehyde enters the cyanosulfidic pathway on surface sulfide minerals under UV to produce lactaldehyde. Strecker synthesis then yields the aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Pyruvate \u2192 Decarboxylation \u2192 Acetaldehyde \u2192 Cyanosulfidic \u2192 Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is fixed to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite at hydrothermal vents. Pyruvate is thermally decarboxylated on pyrite to yield acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde enters the cyanosulfidic pathway to produce lactaldehyde, then Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis yield threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate + Acetaldehyde Aldol \u2192 Reductive Amination Route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to glyoxylate on Fe0 at hydrothermal vents. Acetaldehyde (from FTT or pyruvate decarboxylation) undergoes aldol condensation with glyoxylate on montmorillonite surfaces to form 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate. Reductive amination on Fe0 yields threonine directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate \u2192 Acetaldehyde \u2192 Glyoxylate Aldol \u2192 Reductive Amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate formed by hydrothermal CO2 fixation is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde. Separately, glyoxylate is produced on Fe0. The aldol condensation of acetaldehyde with glyoxylate on montmorillonite yields 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate, which is reductively aminated to threonine on Fe0.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker Route via Formose Lactaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from hydrothermal reduction feeds into the formose reaction to produce glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde reacts with DAP and HCN via the phosphoro-Strecker synthesis to form the aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker Route via Cyanosulfidic Lactaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde from FTT synthesis enters the cyanosulfidic pathway to yield lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde then reacts via the phosphoro-Strecker synthesis with DAP and HCN, followed by hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pure Hydrothermal: CO2 \u2192 Glyoxylate + FTT Acetaldehyde \u2192 Keto Acid \u2192 Threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Both glyoxylate (from Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction) and acetaldehyde (from FTT on magnetite) are produced in the hydrothermal environment. Their aldol condensation at surface interfaces and subsequent reductive amination at hydrothermal Fe0 surfaces complete the synthesis entirely through hydrothermal/near-vent chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose Shortcut: Formaldehyde \u2192 Glycolaldehyde \u2192 Methylglyoxal \u2192 Lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from either hydrothermal or FTT sources enters the formose reaction at the surface, producing glycolaldehyde. Glycolaldehyde condenses with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde, which dehydrates to methylglyoxal and is selectively reduced to lactaldehyde. The Strecker synthesis completes the path to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual Convergence: Pyruvate Decarboxylation + Formose Merge at Lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"This pathway merges two convergent routes to lactaldehyde: (1) the formose chain from hydrothermal formaldehyde through glyceraldehyde and methylglyoxal, and (2) the pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde feeding into the cyanosulfidic route. Both converge at lactaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis to form threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde \u2014 the central C1 building block formed by both formate reduction (rxn_002) and FTT synthesis (rxn_003), consumed by the formose reaction (rxn_007, rxn_008) to build C2 and C3 intermediates.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde \u2014 the key C2 hub formed by FTT synthesis (rxn_003) and pyruvate decarboxylation (rxn_005), feeding into both the aldol route to 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate (rxn_013) and the cyanosulfidic route to lactaldehyde (rxn_016).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde \u2014 the critical C3 aldehyde hub for Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker synthesis of threonine. Formed by two independent routes: methylglyoxal reduction (rxn_010) and cyanosulfidic transformation (rxn_016).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN \u2014 the nitrogen/carbon carrier essential for both Strecker (rxn_011) and phosphoro-Strecker (rxn_015) synthesis. Also participates in cyanosulfidic chemistry (rxn_016).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate \u2014 the C3 alpha-keto acid hub formed by hydrothermal CO2 fixation (rxn_004), feeding acetaldehyde production via decarboxylation (rxn_005). Connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to downstream surface chemistry.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "Threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid, C4H9NO3) is synthesized via a multi-environment prebiotic network. The strategy begins with hydrothermal CO2 reduction to C1 units (formate, formaldehyde, CO) and C3 units (pyruvate) on iron-sulfur minerals. These feed into surface aldol, formose, and Strecker chemistry to build the C4 backbone and install the amino and hydroxyl groups. Two major convergence hubs are lactaldehyde (the Strecker aldehyde precursor) and 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate (the reductive amination precursor). Ten distinct pathways span hydrothermal carbon fixation, Fischer-Tropsch synthesis, formose sugar chemistry, Strecker synthesis, phosphoro-Strecker synthesis, cyanosulfidic chemistry, reductive amination of alpha-keto acids, glyoxylate aldol pathways, decarboxylation-aldol sequences, and wet-dry peptide assembly. Hub molecules (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, HCN, lactaldehyde) interconnect across all three environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "HCOOH", "iupac_name": "formic acid", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanal", "common_name": "methylglyoxal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h3H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropionaldehyde", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H6NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoethanoic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "H2NO3P(NH2)2", "iupac_name": "diamidophosphate", "common_name": "DAP", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO2 adsorbs on greigite surface Fe-Ni-S clusters, analogous to biological [Fe4S4] cofactors. H2 dissociatively adsorbs, and surface hydride transfers to CO2, yielding formate via a surface-bound formate intermediate.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is well established as a prebiotic carbon fixation pathway at alkaline hydrothermal vents, analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway in acetogens. Greigite is structurally similar to biological iron-sulfur clusters (Preiner et al., 2020; Yamaguchi et al., 2014). The Lost City hydrothermal field provides H2-rich, alkaline conditions favorable for this reaction (Sources 15866, 2626)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on mackinawite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing conditions, subseafloor hydrothermal circulation"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced via surface hydride on mackinawite FeS layers. The carboxylate oxygen is activated on the mineral surface, and a two-electron reduction yields formaldehyde and water.", "reasoning": "Sequential reduction of CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde on iron-sulfur minerals follows the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway analogy. Mackinawite is a precursor to greigite and provides layered FeS surfaces for further reduction steps (Roldan et al., 2015). Formaldehyde is a critical C1 building block for prebiotic chemistry (Sources 15634, 6942)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions, CO/H2 gas phase on magnetite surface"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs on magnetite surface, undergoes stepwise hydrogenation via dissociated H2 to form surface methyl and methylene species. Chain growth produces C2 oxygenates (acetaldehyde) alongside C1 oxygenates (formaldehyde).", "reasoning": "Magnetite catalyzes FTT reactions producing aldehydes, alcohols, and hydrocarbons from CO + H2. Magnetite forms at ~360K and is catalytically active for FTT synthesis (Sources 19309, 19315). The Cold Bokkeveld chondrite containing magnetite catalyzes FTT reactions. Acetaldehyde is a key C2 building block for threonine synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "CO2 fixation to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite mixed mineral assemblage", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, multi-step CO2 fixation"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO \u2192 acetyl intermediate \u2192 pyruvate. Greigite mediates the initial reduction steps while magnetite supports C-C coupling. Pyruvate forms via carboxylation of an acetyl-mineral intermediate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on iron-sulfur/iron-oxide mineral assemblages has been demonstrated as a prebiotic analog of the acetyl-CoA pathway. Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub connecting carbon fixation to amino acid synthesis (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2017). Sources (995, 9332, 9334) identify pyruvate as a prebiotically relevant hub molecule."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal decarboxylation, mildly acidic hydrothermal fluids"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation on the pyrite surface. The C2-C3 bond cleaves heterolytically, releasing CO2 and producing acetaldehyde. Pyrite surface stabilizes the transition state via Lewis acid interactions with the keto carbonyl.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of alpha-keto acids is a well-known prebiotic reaction, producing aldehydes that serve as Strecker synthesis substrates. This provides a second convergent route to acetaldehyde from pyruvate (Sources 6940, 995). Pyrite surfaces catalyze such decarboxylation reactions at hydrothermal temperatures."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "CO2 reduction to glyoxylate on elemental iron", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strongly reducing conditions, native iron surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Fe0 provides electrons for CO2 reduction. Two CO2 molecules are sequentially reduced and coupled on the Fe0 surface to yield glyoxylate (OHCCOOH), the simplest alpha-keto acid.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is identified as a prebiotically relevant input alongside pyruvate (Sources 995, 9332, 9334). Fe0 is a strong reductant for CO2 fixation and has been shown to drive reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids (Sources 1026). Glyoxylate formation from CO2 on metallic iron provides the C2 keto-acid needed for aldol routes to threonine."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Formose reaction: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals with Ca(OH)2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline evaporitic pool, formose reaction conditions"}, "mechanism": "Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. Ca(OH)2 provides alkalinity; borate minerals stabilize the glycolaldehyde product by forming borate esters, preventing further uncontrolled oligomerization.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction is a canonical prebiotic pathway for sugar synthesis from formaldehyde. Borate minerals stabilize glycolaldehyde and other sugars, channeling the reaction toward biologically relevant products (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012). This is the entry point for the formose-to-lactaldehyde pathway to threonine (Sources 15634)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface with borate stabilization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde enolizes on the montmorillonite surface; the enolate attacks the formaldehyde carbonyl in a crossed aldol reaction, yielding glyceraldehyde. Borate complexation stabilizes the triose product against retro-aldol.", "reasoning": "The aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde is a key step in the formose reaction network. Montmorillonite catalyzes such condensations (Sources 9431). Glyceraldehyde is a critical C3 intermediate en route to methylglyoxal and then lactaldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Dehydration of glyceraldehyde to methylglyoxal", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalyst under UV", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, no ozone shield, shallow pool"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes UV-assisted dehydration on TiO2 surface. The C2-OH is eliminated as water, generating the alpha-dicarbonyl methylglyoxal (pyruvaldehyde). TiO2 surface generates radical intermediates that facilitate the elimination.", "reasoning": "Methylglyoxal is a known product of glyceraldehyde dehydration and a formose reaction intermediate. UV photocatalysis on TiO2 drives dehydration reactions under early Earth surface conditions with strong UV radiation and no ozone layer (Sources 21187). Methylglyoxal is a direct precursor to lactaldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on sulfide minerals", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "stibnite and other sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly reducing surface pool, H2S as reductant"}, "mechanism": "Methylglyoxal (CH3COCHO) is selectively reduced at the more electrophilic keto carbonyl. H2S donates electrons via the sulfide mineral surface, reducing the C2 keto group to a hydroxyl, yielding lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO) while preserving the aldehyde function.", "reasoning": "Selective reduction of alpha-dicarbonyls is facilitated by sulfide minerals acting as electron mediators. H2S provides reducing equivalents in cyanosulfidic chemistry (Sources 9381, 9382, 10209). The selective reduction of one carbonyl over another on mineral surfaces is analogous to enzymatic selectivity."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH3 to threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface concentrates reactants", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ambient evaporitic pool, pH 7-9"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. HCN then undergoes nucleophilic addition to the imine C=N bond, yielding the alpha-aminonitrile (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile). Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants and stabilizes the imine intermediate.", "reasoning": "The Strecker reaction is the most widely studied prebiotic pathway for amino acid synthesis (Sources 6940, 6942, 985). Lactaldehyde is the appropriate aldehyde for threonine formation. Imine-like intermediates are short-lived under aqueous conditions but are driven to completion (Sources 1026). Montmorillonite clays concentrate and catalyze such reactions (Sources 9431)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis, mildly acidic to neutral pH, wet-dry cycling may concentrate products"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-CN) of the aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to an amide (-CONH2), then to a carboxylic acid (-COOH), releasing ammonia. This yields threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid).", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the terminal step of the Strecker synthesis and occurs readily in aqueous solution at moderate temperatures and neutral to mildly acidic pH (Wolman et al., 1971; Sources 6940, 23270). This completes the Strecker route to threonine."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Aldol condensation of glyoxylate and acetaldehyde to 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with phosphate buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 6-8, phosphate-buffered evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde enolizes in the slightly alkaline phosphate-buffered environment. The enolate attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of glyoxylate in a crossed aldol condensation, forming the C4 alpha-keto-beta-hydroxy acid (2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate), the alpha-keto acid corresponding to threonine.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate and pyruvate are identified as prebiotically relevant inputs in protometabolic networks (Sources 995, 9332, 9334). Aldol condensation of alpha-keto acids with aldehydes produces higher alpha-keto acids that serve as reductive amination substrates. This mirrors the biological connection between TCA cycle intermediates and amino acid biosynthesis (Sources 6987, 6944)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reductive amination of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine on Fe0", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH < 7, imine-like intermediate formed transiently"}, "mechanism": "NH3 attacks the keto carbonyl of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate, forming a transient imine (Schiff base). Fe0 provides reducing equivalents to reduce the C=N bond to C-NH2, completing the reductive amination to threonine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids by NH3 on Fe0 under aqueous conditions (pH < 7) is a demonstrated prebiotic pathway for amino acid synthesis (Sources 1026). Fe0 serves as both reductant and surface catalyst. This mimics biological transamination and represents the alpha-keto acid route to threonine (Sources 6940, 6943, 6987)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Phosphoro-Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + DAP + HCN to threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_020", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate mineral surface, pH 7", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH, DAP as phosphorylating/activating agent"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with DAP to form an N-phosphoroamino intermediate, which then reacts with HCN to yield N-phosphoroaminonitrile. Under acidic conditions (pH 1.5), the phosphoro group is lost yielding the free aminonitrile. The pathway selectively targets aldehydes over ketones, avoiding unnatural alpha,alpha-disubstituted amino acids.", "reasoning": "The phosphoro-Strecker synthesis is a prebiotically plausible variation of the Strecker reaction that uses diamidophosphate (DAP) as an activating agent (Sources 21192, 21193). This pathway operates at neutral pH and selectively produces aminonitriles from aldehydes, providing a second convergent route to the threonine aminonitrile intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Direct Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde to threonine precursor via cyanosulfidic intermediate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite, MoS2)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals + UV on TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic conditions, H2S/HCN co-present"}, "mechanism": "In the cyanosulfidic scenario, acetaldehyde reacts with HCN to form cyanohydrin (lactonitrile). Under UV irradiation, H2S-mediated reduction generates the hydroxylated aldehyde (lactaldehyde) via a series of radical and sulfide-mediated transformations. This provides an alternative pathway from acetaldehyde to the key Strecker aldehyde.", "reasoning": "The cyanosulfidic scenario (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland and co-workers) provides UV-driven pathways from simple feedstocks (HCN, H2S, aldehydes) to amino acid precursors (Sources 9381, 9382, 9376, 16400). This represents an alternative surface route to lactaldehyde, complementing the formose-based pathway."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 \u2192 Formate \u2192 Formaldehyde \u2192 Formose \u2192 Strecker Route", "description": "CO2 is reduced to formate at hydrothermal vents on greigite, then further reduced to formaldehyde on mackinawite. Formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where formose chemistry builds glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde. Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3 on lactaldehyde produces the aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch Acetaldehyde \u2192 Cyanosulfidic \u2192 Strecker Route", "description": "CO and H2 undergo FTT synthesis on magnetite to yield acetaldehyde and formaldehyde. Acetaldehyde enters the cyanosulfidic pathway on surface sulfide minerals under UV to produce lactaldehyde. Strecker synthesis then yields the aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_016", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal Pyruvate \u2192 Decarboxylation \u2192 Acetaldehyde \u2192 Cyanosulfidic \u2192 Strecker", "description": "CO2 is fixed to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite at hydrothermal vents. Pyruvate is thermally decarboxylated on pyrite to yield acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde enters the cyanosulfidic pathway to produce lactaldehyde, then Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis yield threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_016", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Glyoxylate + Acetaldehyde Aldol \u2192 Reductive Amination Route", "description": "CO2 is reduced to glyoxylate on Fe0 at hydrothermal vents. Acetaldehyde (from FTT or pyruvate decarboxylation) undergoes aldol condensation with glyoxylate on montmorillonite surfaces to form 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate. Reductive amination on Fe0 yields threonine directly.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_003", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_009", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Pyruvate \u2192 Acetaldehyde \u2192 Glyoxylate Aldol \u2192 Reductive Amination", "description": "Pyruvate formed by hydrothermal CO2 fixation is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde. Separately, glyoxylate is produced on Fe0. The aldol condensation of acetaldehyde with glyoxylate on montmorillonite yields 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate, which is reductively aminated to threonine on Fe0.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_017", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Phosphoro-Strecker Route via Formose Lactaldehyde", "description": "Formaldehyde from hydrothermal reduction feeds into the formose reaction to produce glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde reacts with DAP and HCN via the phosphoro-Strecker synthesis to form the aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_015", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Phosphoro-Strecker Route via Cyanosulfidic Lactaldehyde", "description": "Acetaldehyde from FTT synthesis enters the cyanosulfidic pathway to yield lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde then reacts via the phosphoro-Strecker synthesis with DAP and HCN, followed by hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_016", "rxn_015", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Pure Hydrothermal: CO2 \u2192 Glyoxylate + FTT Acetaldehyde \u2192 Keto Acid \u2192 Threonine", "description": "Both glyoxylate (from Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction) and acetaldehyde (from FTT on magnetite) are produced in the hydrothermal environment. Their aldol condensation at surface interfaces and subsequent reductive amination at hydrothermal Fe0 surfaces complete the synthesis entirely through hydrothermal/near-vent chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_003", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_009", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Formose Shortcut: Formaldehyde \u2192 Glycolaldehyde \u2192 Methylglyoxal \u2192 Lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker", "description": "Formaldehyde from either hydrothermal or FTT sources enters the formose reaction at the surface, producing glycolaldehyde. Glycolaldehyde condenses with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde, which dehydrates to methylglyoxal and is selectively reduced to lactaldehyde. The Strecker synthesis completes the path to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mo