ormose-Strecker route starting from formaldehyde. Assumes formaldehyde is available, skipping hydrothermal steps. rxn_010 remains the weakest link. Otherwise chemically sound with well-established formose and Strecker reactions.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Include hydrothermal source for formaldehyde\", \"Consider alternative lactaldehyde synthesis\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n      \"feedback\": \"Most comprehensive pathway demonstrating network convergence. Dual hydrothermal inputs (formate\u2192formaldehyde and pyruvate\u2192acetaldehyde) merge at lactaldehyde for Strecker synthesis. Shows good network interconnectivity. Still limited by rxn_010 quality, but the overall strategy is sound and well-aligned with multi-environment prebiotic models.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Strengthen rxn_010 mechanistic justification\", \"Consider adding alternative convergence at lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde + formaldehyde aldol\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-designed synthesis network with strong topology, good convergence, and solid literature alignment. The network correctly identifies and implements the major prebiotic routes to threonine: Strecker synthesis, phosphoro-Strecker synthesis, and reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids, all of which are explicitly supported by the literature. Hub molecules (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, HCN, lactaldehyde) are well-chosen and properly interconnected. The environmental Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical flow is well-implemented in most pathways. Two significant weaknesses: (1) rxn_016 (cyanosulfidic route to lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde + HCN + H2S) is mechanistically unsound\u2014the product should be a cyanohydrin, not an aldehyde, which undermines pathways P2, P3, and P7; (2) CO (mol_006) is used as input in rxn_003 but never produced by any network reaction, creating a dangling dependency. Additionally, rxn_010 (H2S reduction of methylglyoxal) lacks strong precedent for selective ketone reduction. Despite these issues, 6 of 10 pathways achieve approval, and the strongest routes (P5, P6, P4) are chemically robust and well-supported by literature. The inclusion of DAP-mediated phosphoro-Strecker chemistry is a notable strength, directly supported by recent literature.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.88,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.85\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_002": 0.8, "rxn_007": 0.9, "rxn_008": 0.88, "rxn_009": 0.75, "rxn_010": 0.65, "rxn_011": 0.9, "rxn_012": 0.85}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.78, "pathway_coherence": 0.83, "environmental_progression": 0.9, "target_achievement": 0.85, "overall_confidence": 0.82, "feedback": "Well-structured pathway with clean Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical flow. The weakest link is rxn_010 (selective reduction of methylglyoxal ketone by H2S on sulfide minerals to give lactaldehyde), which lacks strong mechanistic precedent for selective carbonyl reduction. All other steps are well-supported by formose and Strecker chemistry literature.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "suggestions": ["Consider alternative reductants for methylglyo