-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"H4NO3P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"diamidophosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAP\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9N3O4P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"N-phosphoro-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-phosphoro-threonine-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxythreonine keto acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(6)4(7)8/h2,5H,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is adsorbed on the greigite (Fe3S4) surface, which acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 to formate (HCOO-) via surface-bound formate intermediates. The alkaline vent pH gradient provides thermodynamic driving force.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is one of the best-established prebiotic carbon fixation reactions. Experimental demonstrations by Roldan et al. (2015) showed that greigite surfaces catalyze CO2 reduction to formate and methanol under mild hydrothermal conditions. This mirrors the acetyl-CoA pathway's first step in acetogens (Preiner et al., 2020; Weiss et al., 2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate dehydration to CO on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"450-550K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"higher-temperature zone near black smoker vents\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate adsorbed on the pyrite (FeS2) surface undergoes thermally driven dehydration, releasing CO and H2O. The pyrite surface stabilizes the transition state for C-O bond cleavage. This is analogous to the biological formate dehydrogenase reaction run in reverse at high temperature.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal dehydration of formate to CO on iron-sulfide surfaces at elevated temperatures is supported by experiments in hydrothermal simulations (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). CO is an essential C1 feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-Type chemistry and the prebiotic analog of the acetyl-CoA pathway. This reaction ensures CO is produced within the network, resolving the need for an endogenous CO source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis of formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-Type conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal zone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO and H2 adsorb on the magnetite (Fe3O4) surface, where stepwise hydrogenation of CO produces surface-bound formyl (HCO*) and hydroxymethyl (H2CO*) species. Formaldehyde (HCHO) is released as the simplest FTT oxygenate product. Magnetite provides the catalytic iron sites necessary for CO activation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis of formaldehyde and other simple oxygenates on magnetite is well-documented. McCollom et al. (1999) demonstrated that magnetite catalyzes FTT reactions producing a range of C1-C4 oxygenates including formaldehyde and methanol. The Cold Bokkeveld carbonaceous chondrite, containing magnetite, also showed FTT catalytic activity (Sources 19309, 19315). Magnetite forms at ~360K during serpentinization.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite-magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite + magnetite mixed mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, multi-step surface-catalyzed reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction on Fe-S/Fe-O mineral surfaces proceeds through formate \u2192 acetate \u2192 pyruvate via surface-bound intermediates. CO2 is first reduced to formate, then to surface-bound CO, which undergoes carbonylation and further reduction. The multi-step process mirrors the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway and reverse incomplete TCA cycle. Pyruvate (CH3COCOOH) is a key C3 \u03b1-keto acid hub.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on iron-sulfur/iron-oxide minerals has been demonstrated by Cody et al. (2000) using FeS and iron-nickel alloy under hydrothermal conditions (250\u00b0C, high pressure). Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated native iron-driven CO2 fixation to pyruvate and other metabolites at 100\u00b0C in aqueous solution, and Muchowska et al. (2017) showed that Fe0 promotes reductive amination from \u03b1-keto acids. This reaction is central to proto-metabolic carbon fixation (Sources 1026, 6987).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal decarboxylation in hydrothermal fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate (CH3COCOOH) undergoes thermal decarboxylation at the mineral surface, releasing CO2 and producing acetaldehyde (CH3CHO). The mechanism involves protonation of the \u03b2-carbonyl, facilitating loss of CO2 from the \u03b1-keto acid. On magnetite surfaces, the Fe(II/III) sites act as Lewis acids stabilizing the transition state.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde is well-established in prebiotic chemistry and occurs readily at hydrothermal temperatures (>80\u00b0C). This has been demonstrated in experimental studies of amino acid and keto acid stability in hydrothermal systems (Barge et al., 2019; Sources 2655, 2656). The reaction is the prebiotic analog of pyruvate decarboxylase and provides acetaldehyde, a critical C2 building block.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"FTT synthesis producing C2 oxygenates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO and H2 undergo Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis on magnetite, producing a distribution of C1-C4 oxygenated products. Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) is formed through chain growth from surface-bound C1 intermediates (formyl \u2192 hydroxymethyl \u2192 methyl) followed by CO insertion and hydrogenation to give the C2 aldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT synthesis on magnetite is known to produce a range of oxygenates including methanol, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and acetone (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). The Cold Bokkeveld chondrite magnetite experiments also showed C2+ products (Sources 19309, 19315). This provides a direct hydrothermal route to acetaldehyde independent of pyruvate decarboxylation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to glyoxylic acid on mackinawite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite/greigite mixed mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, reductive CO2 fixation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two CO2 molecules are sequentially reduced on the FeS/Fe3S4 surface. The first CO2 is reduced to formate/CO, which then undergoes carbonylation and partial reduction to produce glyoxylic acid (OHCCOOH), the simplest \u03b1-keto acid. Glyoxylic acid is structurally the C2 analog of pyruvate and a key hub in proto-metabolic networks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a central metabolite in multiple prebiotic proto-metabolic scenarios, including the glyoxylate cycle and reductive TCA cycle analogs. Its formation from CO2 on iron-sulfur minerals is proposed by Muchowska et al. (2019) and Springsteen et al. (2018). Glyoxylate and pyruvate are the two key prebiotically relevant \u03b1-keto acid inputs identified in proto-metabolic networks (Sources 995, 9332, 9334).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and Ca(OH)2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool or volcanic hot spring, alkaline conditions pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde (HCHO) undergo umpolung-type condensation (the formose reaction). In the presence of Ca(OH)2 or borate, one formaldehyde is activated as a nucleophilic carbanion equivalent (Breslow's 1,2-enediol mechanism), which attacks the carbonyl of the second formaldehyde to yield glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO). Borate minerals stabilize the product by complexation with the diol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction is a well-established prebiotic sugar synthesis discovered by Butlerov (1861). Borate stabilization of sugars including glycolaldehyde was demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004). The reaction proceeds in warm alkaline conditions consistent with evaporitic or hot spring environments. Glycolaldehyde is the simplest sugar and a key building block (Sources 15634, 16400).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose aldol: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool, borate stabilization of products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) enolizes under alkaline conditions to form an enediol, which acts as a nucleophilic C2 unit that attacks formaldehyde. The aldol addition produces glyceraldehyde (HOCH2CH(OH)CHO), a C3 triose. Borate minerals complex with the vicinal diol of the product, stabilizing glyceraldehyde against further aldol branching and retro-aldol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The aldol extension of glycolaldehyde by formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde is a key step in the formose reaction well-studied by Breslow (1959) and confirmed under prebiotic conditions by Ricardo et al. (2004) and Kim et al. (2011). Borate stabilization is critical for channeling formose products toward useful C3 sugars rather than tar (Sources 16400). Glyceraldehyde is also identified in cyanosulfidic proto-metabolic networks (Patel et al., 2015; Sources 9376).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde dehydration to methylglyoxal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface (acid sites)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild heating in evaporitic pool or geothermal field, clay-catalyzed elimination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde (HOCH2CH(OH)CHO) undergoes acid-catalyzed dehydration on montmorillonite clay surfaces. The C3-OH is eliminated as H2O, producing methylglyoxal (CH3COCHO). The Br\u00f8nsted acid sites on montmorillonite promote protonation of the hydroxyl leaving group. This reaction is thermodynamically favorable and occurs readily even under mild conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The dehydration of glyceraldehyde to methylglyoxal (pyruvaldehyde) is a well-known degradation pathway that occurs readily in aqueous solution at elevated temperature and acidic pH. This reaction has been documented in sugar chemistry by Thornalley (1996) and is recognized in prebiotic contexts as a route from triose sugars to reactive dicarbonyl intermediates. Montmorillonite acid sites catalyze dehydration reactions (Sources 9431).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Methylglyoxal selective reduction to lactaldehyde on metallic iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe0) and FeS surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, surface-controlled selectivity via steric binding\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Methylglyoxal (CH3-CO-CHO) adsorbs on Fe0/FeS mineral surfaces through the more sterically accessible ketone carbonyl. Electron transfer from Fe0 (Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ + 2e-) generates surface-bound hydride equivalents that selectively reduce the ketone to an alcohol, yielding lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO). The aldehyde group, oriented away from the surface, is less accessible for reduction. This surface-controlled regioselectivity is analogous to heterogeneous catalytic selectivity in modern chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe0 (metallic iron) is established as a potent prebiotic reductant capable of reducing \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids via reductive amination (Wang et al., 2011; Barge et al., 2019; Sources 1026). The selective reduction of one carbonyl in a dicarbonyl compound on heterogeneous metal surfaces is documented in modern catalysis. Under prebiotic conditions, Fe0 was abundant from meteoritic iron and would have been present in surface environments near hydrothermal outflows. The ketone-selective reduction is plausible based on preferential surface binding of the less sterically hindered keto group.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis of lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"FTT synthesis producing C3 oxygenated products including hydroxy-aldehydes\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO and H2 undergo Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis on magnetite surfaces, producing a product distribution that includes C3 oxygenated compounds. Lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal, CH3CH(OH)CHO) forms through chain growth from C1 surface intermediates: formyl \u2192 C2 aldehyde \u2192 hydroxylation and extension to give the C3 hydroxy-aldehyde. Oxygen incorporation during chain growth yields the 2-hydroxy substitution pattern.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT synthesis on magnetite produces a range of oxygenated organic products including alcohols, aldehydes, and hydroxy-compounds up to C4 and beyond (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). Hydroxy-aldehydes are among the observed product types. While lactaldehyde specifically has not been isolated from FTT experiments, the product distribution from FTT includes C3 oxygenated species, and hydroxy-aldehyde formation is thermodynamically and mechanistically consistent with the FTT chain-growth mechanism (Sources 19309, 19315). This provides a direct hydrothermal route to lactaldehyde bypassing the formose pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH3 to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly alkaline pH (7-9), evaporitic pool environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The Strecker synthesis proceeds in two steps: (1) lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO) reacts with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base, CH3CH(OH)CH=NH) with loss of H2O; (2) HCN adds to the electrophilic imine carbon (nucleophilic addition) to form the \u03b1-aminonitrile product, 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (CH3CH(OH)CH(NH2)CN). Montmorillonite surfaces concentrate reactants and catalyze imine formation through acid-base catalysis at clay edge sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker reaction is universally recognized as the most important prebiotic route to \u03b1-amino acids (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957). Its application to threonine synthesis from lactaldehyde is explicit in the literature as the natural Strecker route to hydroxy-amino acids (Sources 6940, 6942, 985). The reaction requires the aldehyde (lactaldehyde), NH3, and HCN, all of which are prebiotically available. Montmorillonite catalysis of amine-aldehyde condensations is documented (Sources 9431). Short-lived imine intermediates drive the reaction to completion under aqueous conditions (Sources 1026).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, prolonged aqueous exposure, wet-dry cycling to concentrate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-CN) of the threonine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to an amide (-CONH2) via nucleophilic addition of water, then to the carboxylic acid (-COOH) with loss of NH3. The overall transformation converts 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid (threonine). The hydrolysis is thermodynamically favorable and occurs spontaneously in aqueous solution over hours to days at ambient temperature.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the well-established second step of the Strecker synthesis. This has been demonstrated under a wide range of prebiotic conditions (Miller, 1957; Wolman et al., 1971; Sources 23270, 6940). The hydrolysis can be acid-catalyzed (pH < 3) or base-catalyzed (pH > 10), but also proceeds at neutral pH over longer timescales. Wet-dry cycling in prebiotic pools can facilitate this process (Sources 512).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + DAP + HCN to N-phosphoro-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"struvite (MgNH4PO4\u00b76H2O) as phosphate source/surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH 7, evaporitic pool conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The phosphoro-Strecker synthesis involves: (1) diamidophosphate (DAP) reacts with the aldehyde group of lactaldehyde to form a phosphoramidate-aldehyde adduct; (2) intramolecular cyclization and HCN addition produce the N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate. DAP acts as both the nitrogen source and a phosphorylating agent, replacing free NH3. This pathway selectively targets aldehydes over ketones, avoiding unnatural disubstituted products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The phosphoro-Strecker synthesis was recently demonstrated by Krishnamurthy et al. (2017) and described as a plausible prebiotic pathway that produces N-phosphoroaminonitriles from aldehydes, DAP, and HCN at neutral pH. This pathway is directly relevant to threonine synthesis from lactaldehyde (Sources 21192, 21193). DAP itself has been shown to form under prebiotic conditions from phosphate minerals and ammonia. The selectivity for aldehydes ensures biologically relevant \u03b1-amino acids.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of N-phosphoro-threonine-aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH 13 for N-phosphoramidic acid formation, then neutral hydrolysis; or pH 1.5 for aminonitrile release followed by hydrolysis (Sources 21192)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate can follow multiple hydrolysis routes depending on pH: (1) at pH 13, hydrolysis yields an N-phosphoramidic acid which further hydrolyzes to the amino acid; (2) at pH 1.5, the phosphoryl group is cleaved to release the aminonitrile, which then undergoes standard nitrile hydrolysis to threonine. Both routes converge on threonine as the final product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The pH-dependent hydrolysis pathways of phosphoro-Strecker intermediates are detailed by Krishnamurthy et al. (2017), who showed that different products (aminothioamides at pH 7 with H2S, N-phosphoramidic acids at pH 13, aminonitriles at pH 1.5) can all ultimately yield amino acids (Sources 21192, 21193). In a prebiotic pool environment, natural pH fluctuations from volcanic acid rain or mineral dissolution could drive these transformations.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glyoxylic acid and acetaldehyde to 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and apatite surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH 8-9, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) enolizes under mildly alkaline conditions to form the nucleophilic enol (CH2=CHOH). This C2 nucleophile attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of glyoxylic acid (OHC-COOH) in an aldol addition, yielding 2-hydroxy-4-oxobutanoic acid initially. Under surface-catalyzed conditions on montmorillonite, keto-enol tautomerization and rearrangement on the clay surface can produce the thermodynamically more stable 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid (the \u03b1-keto acid of threonine). The phosphate mineral surface provides base catalysis for enolization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensations between \u03b1-keto acids and aldehydes are central to proto-metabolic networks. Springsteen et al. (2018) and Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated that glyoxylate and pyruvate serve as prebiotically relevant starting materials that undergo aldol chemistry to produce C3-C5 metabolic intermediates (Sources 995, 9332, 9334). The specific aldol of glyoxylate + acetaldehyde to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid is a plausible extension of this chemistry, as both substrates are abundantly produced in hydrothermal environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid to threonine on metallic iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic pH 5-7, surface of meteoritic iron\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-keto acid (3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid, CH3CH(OH)COCOOH) reacts with NH3 at the keto group to form an imine intermediate (CH3CH(OH)C(=NH)COOH). Fe0 acts as a stoichiometric reductant (Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ + 2e-), providing electrons for reduction of the C=N imine bond to give the C-NH2 amine, yielding threonine. The reaction is analogous to biological transamination but uses NH3 directly.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids by metallic iron (Fe0) with NH3 and bifunctional amines has been experimentally demonstrated by Wang et al. (2011, Sources 1026). They showed that Fe0 reduces keto acids (R-CO-COOH) to amino acids in aqueous solution at pH < 7, with imine-like intermediates driving the reaction. This mirrors biological transamination and has been extended to multiple proteinogenic amino acids (Sources 6940, 6944, 6987). The use of Fe0 as reductant is plausible given abundant meteoritic iron on early Earth.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation \u2192 Formose \u2192 Strecker threonine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete pathway from CO2 through hydrothermal C1 fixation (greigite \u2192 formate \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde), then surface formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde, dehydration to methylglyoxal, reduction to lactaldehyde, and final Strecker synthesis with HCN + NH3 to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation \u2192 Formose \u2192 Phosphoro-Strecker threonine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Same upstream as P1 (CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde) but uses the phosphoro-Strecker route with DAP instead of free NH3 for the terminal amino acid synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct FTT lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker threonine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis on magnetite directly produces lactaldehyde from CO + H2, bypassing the formose pathway entirely. Lactaldehyde then enters the classical Strecker synthesis with HCN + NH3.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct FTT lactaldehyde \u2192 Phosphoro-Strecker threonine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"FTT synthesis produces lactaldehyde directly, which then undergoes phosphoro-Strecker synthesis with DAP + HCN to yield threonine via N-phosphoroaminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid aldol \u2192 Reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is synthesized from CO2 hydrothermally, then decarboxylated to acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation with glyoxylic acid to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid, which is reductively aminated on Fe0 surfaces to yield threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid aldol \u2192 Reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde is produced directly via FTT synthesis on magnetite. Combined with hydrothermally-derived glyoxylic acid, the aldol product (threonine's \u03b1-keto acid) is reductively aminated on Fe0 to yield threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT formaldehyde \u2192 Formose glycolaldehyde \u2192 Full formose-Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal FTT provides formaldehyde, which undergoes formose dimerization to glycolaldehyde on borate minerals. Glycolaldehyde extends with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde, which dehydrates to methylglyoxal, is reduced to lactaldehyde, and enters Strecker synthesis. This pathway emphasizes the formose hub of glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 Formose methylglyoxal \u2192 Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate from hydrothermal CO2 fixation is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde. Independently, formaldehyde from FTT undergoes formose to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde. Glyceraldehyde dehydrates to methylglyoxal, which is reduced to lactaldehyde on Fe0. Lactaldehyde enters Strecker synthesis. This pathway shows how pyruvate connects to the acetaldehyde hub, though the terminal steps proceed through the formose-derived intermediates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Complete FTT \u2192 Direct lactaldehyde \u2192 Reductive amination bypass\",\n      \"description\": \"FTT produces both lactaldehyde (C3 hydroxy-aldehyde) and acetaldehyde on magnetite. Glyoxylic acid from mackinawite combines with acetaldehyde in an aldol to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid, which is reductively aminated. Simultaneously, FTT lactaldehyde provides a parallel Strecker route. Both converge on threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate \u2192 Acetaldehyde + Glyoxylate \u2192 \u03b1-Keto acid \u2192 Reductive amination (pure metabolic analog)\",\n      \"description\": \"This pathway most closely mirrors biological threonine biosynthesis analogs via proto-metabolic chemistry. Pyruvate and glyoxylic acid are both produced from CO2 on iron-sulfur minerals. Pyruvate is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, which undergoes aldol with glyoxylate to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid. Reductive amination on Fe0 with NH3 produces threonine, mimicking biological transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde - key C1 building block produced hydrothermally, consumed in formose chemistry\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde - C2 hub produced by two independent routes (pyruvate decarboxylation and FTT), feeds into \u03b1-keto acid aldol chemistry\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde - critical C3 aldehyde hub where formose and FTT pathways converge; feeds directly into both Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker terminal syntheses\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen cyanide - essential C1+N building block consumed in both Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Carbon monoxide - C1 intermediate produced from formate dehydration, consumed in all three FTT syntheses (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "Threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid, C4H9NO3) is synthesized through a convergent prebiotic network centered on the key intermediate lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal), which serves as the C3 aldehyde input for Strecker-type and phosphoro-Strecker amino acid syntheses. The network begins with hydrothermal CO2 fixation on iron-sulfur minerals to generate C1 building blocks (formate, CO, formaldehyde) and C2-C3 intermediates (acetaldehyde, pyruvate). These feed into surface formose chemistry to produce glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, and ultimately lactaldehyde via methylglyoxal reduction. Fischer-Tropsch-Type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite provides a parallel hydrothermal route directly to lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde then converges with HCN and NH3 in classic Strecker synthesis, or with diamidophosphate (DAP) and HCN in the phosphoro-Strecker pathway, to yield threonine aminonitrile intermediates that hydrolyze to threonine. An additional reductive amination route converts glyoxylate-acetaldehyde aldol products to threonine on metallic iron surfaces. Ten distinct pathways arise from combinatorial selection of upstream C1 fixation routes, lactaldehyde formation methods, and terminal Strecker/phosphoro-Strecker/reductive-amination steps, all interconnecting across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanal", "common_name": "methylglyoxal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h3H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "H4NO3P", "iupac_name": "diamidophosphate", "common_name": "DAP", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H9N3O4P", "iupac_name": "N-phosphoro-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "N-phosphoro-threonine-aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoethanoic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxythreonine keto acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(6)4(7)8/h2,5H,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is adsorbed on the greigite (Fe3S4) surface, which acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 to formate (HCOO-) via surface-bound formate intermediates. The alkaline vent pH gradient provides thermodynamic driving force.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is one of the best-established prebiotic carbon fixation reactions. Experimental demonstrations by Roldan et al. (2015) showed that greigite surfaces catalyze CO2 reduction to formate and methanol under mild hydrothermal conditions. This mirrors the acetyl-CoA pathway's first step in acetogens (Preiner et al., 2020; Weiss et al., 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate dehydration to CO on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "450-550K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "higher-temperature zone near black smoker vents"}, "mechanism": "Formate adsorbed on the pyrite (FeS2) surface undergoes thermally driven dehydration, releasing CO and H2O. The pyrite surface stabilizes the transition state for C-O bond cleavage. This is analogous to the biological formate dehydrogenase reaction run in reverse at high temperature.", "reasoning": "Thermal dehydration of formate to CO on iron-sulfide surfaces at elevated temperatures is supported by experiments in hydrothermal simulations (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). CO is an essential C1 feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-Type chemistry and the prebiotic analog of the acetyl-CoA pathway. This reaction ensures CO is produced within the network, resolving the need for an endogenous CO source."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis of formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-Type conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal zone"}, "mechanism": "CO and H2 adsorb on the magnetite (Fe3O4) surface, where stepwise hydrogenation of CO produces surface-bound formyl (HCO*) and hydroxymethyl (H2CO*) species. Formaldehyde (HCHO) is released as the simplest FTT oxygenate product. Magnetite provides the catalytic iron sites necessary for CO activation.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis of formaldehyde and other simple oxygenates on magnetite is well-documented. McCollom et al. (1999) demonstrated that magnetite catalyzes FTT reactions producing a range of C1-C4 oxygenates including formaldehyde and methanol. The Cold Bokkeveld carbonaceous chondrite, containing magnetite, also showed FTT catalytic activity (Sources 19309, 19315). Magnetite forms at ~360K during serpentinization."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite-magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite + magnetite mixed mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, multi-step surface-catalyzed reduction"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction on Fe-S/Fe-O mineral surfaces proceeds through formate \u2192 acetate \u2192 pyruvate via surface-bound intermediates. CO2 is first reduced to formate, then to surface-bound CO, which undergoes carbonylation and further reduction. The multi-step process mirrors the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway and reverse incomplete TCA cycle. Pyruvate (CH3COCOOH) is a key C3 \u03b1-keto acid hub.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on iron-sulfur/iron-oxide minerals has been demonstrated by Cody et al. (2000) using FeS and iron-nickel alloy under hydrothermal conditions (250\u00b0C, high pressure). Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated native iron-driven CO2 fixation to pyruvate and other metabolites at 100\u00b0C in aqueous solution, and Muchowska et al. (2017) showed that Fe0 promotes reductive amination from \u03b1-keto acids. This reaction is central to proto-metabolic carbon fixation (Sources 1026, 6987)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal decarboxylation in hydrothermal fluid"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate (CH3COCOOH) undergoes thermal decarboxylation at the mineral surface, releasing CO2 and producing acetaldehyde (CH3CHO). The mechanism involves protonation of the \u03b2-carbonyl, facilitating loss of CO2 from the \u03b1-keto acid. On magnetite surfaces, the Fe(II/III) sites act as Lewis acids stabilizing the transition state.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde is well-established in prebiotic chemistry and occurs readily at hydrothermal temperatures (>80\u00b0C). This has been demonstrated in experimental studies of amino acid and keto acid stability in hydrothermal systems (Barge et al., 2019; Sources 2655, 2656). The reaction is the prebiotic analog of pyruvate decarboxylase and provides acetaldehyde, a critical C2 building block."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "FTT synthesis producing C2 oxygenates"}, "mechanism": "CO and H2 undergo Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis on magnetite, producing a distribution of C1-C4 oxygenated products. Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) is formed through chain growth from surface-bound C1 intermediates (formyl \u2192 hydroxymethyl \u2192 methyl) followed by CO insertion and hydrogenation to give the C2 aldehyde.", "reasoning": "FTT synthesis on magnetite is known to produce a range of oxygenates including methanol, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and acetone (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). The Cold Bokkeveld chondrite magnetite experiments also showed C2+ products (Sources 19309, 19315). This provides a direct hydrothermal route to acetaldehyde independent of pyruvate decarboxylation."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "CO2 reduction to glyoxylic acid on mackinawite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite/greigite mixed mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, reductive CO2 fixation"}, "mechanism": "Two CO2 molecules are sequentially reduced on the FeS/Fe3S4 surface. The first CO2 is reduced to formate/CO, which then undergoes carbonylation and partial reduction to produce glyoxylic acid (OHCCOOH), the simplest \u03b1-keto acid. Glyoxylic acid is structurally the C2 analog of pyruvate and a key hub in proto-metabolic networks.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a central metabolite in multiple prebiotic proto-metabolic scenarios, including the glyoxylate cycle and reductive TCA cycle analogs. Its formation from CO2 on iron-sulfur minerals is proposed by Muchowska et al. (2019) and Springsteen et al. (2018). Glyoxylate and pyruvate are the two key prebiotically relevant \u03b1-keto acid inputs identified in proto-metabolic networks (Sources 995, 9332, 9334)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formose reaction: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and Ca(OH)2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or volcanic hot spring, alkaline conditions pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde (HCHO) undergo umpolung-type condensation (the formose reaction). In the presence of Ca(OH)2 or borate, one formaldehyde is activated as a nucleophilic carbanion equivalent (Breslow's 1,2-enediol mechanism), which attacks the carbonyl of the second formaldehyde to yield glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO). Borate minerals stabilize the product by complexation with the diol.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction is a well-established prebiotic sugar synthesis discovered by Butlerov (1861). Borate stabilization of sugars including glycolaldehyde was demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004). The reaction proceeds in warm alkaline conditions consistent with evaporitic or hot spring environments. Glycolaldehyde is the simplest sugar and a key building block (Sources 15634, 16400)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Formose aldol: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool, borate stabilization of products"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) enolizes under alkaline conditions to form an enediol, which acts as a nucleophilic C2 unit that attacks formaldehyde. The aldol addition produces glyceraldehyde (HOCH2CH(OH)CHO), a C3 triose. Borate minerals complex with the vicinal diol of the product, stabilizing glyceraldehyde against further aldol branching and retro-aldol.", "reasoning": "The aldol extension of glycolaldehyde by formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde is a key step in the formose reaction well-studied by Breslow (1959) and confirmed under prebiotic conditions by Ricardo et al. (2004) and Kim et al. (2011). Borate stabilization is critical for channeling formose products toward useful C3 sugars rather than tar (Sources 16400). Glyceraldehyde is also identified in cyanosulfidic proto-metabolic networks (Patel et al., 2015; Sources 9376)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Glyceraldehyde dehydration to methylglyoxal", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface (acid sites)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild heating in evaporitic pool or geothermal field, clay-catalyzed elimination"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde (HOCH2CH(OH)CHO) undergoes acid-catalyzed dehydration on montmorillonite clay surfaces. The C3-OH is eliminated as H2O, producing methylglyoxal (CH3COCHO). The Br\u00f8nsted acid sites on montmorillonite promote protonation of the hydroxyl leaving group. This reaction is thermodynamically favorable and occurs readily even under mild conditions.", "reasoning": "The dehydration of glyceraldehyde to methylglyoxal (pyruvaldehyde) is a well-known degradation pathway that occurs readily in aqueous solution at elevated temperature and acidic pH. This reaction has been documented in sugar chemistry by Thornalley (1996) and is recognized in prebiotic contexts as a route from triose sugars to reactive dicarbonyl intermediates. Montmorillonite acid sites catalyze dehydration reactions (Sources 9431)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Methylglyoxal selective reduction to lactaldehyde on metallic iron", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe0) and FeS surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly acidic to neutral pH, surface-controlled selectivity via steric binding"}, "mechanism": "Methylglyoxal (CH3-CO-CHO) adsorbs on Fe0/FeS mineral surfaces through the more sterically accessible ketone carbonyl. Electron transfer from Fe0 (Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ + 2e-) generates surface-bound hydride equivalents that selectively reduce the ketone to an alcohol, yielding lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO). The aldehyde group, oriented away from the surface, is less accessible for reduction. This surface-controlled regioselectivity is analogous to heterogeneous catalytic selectivity in modern chemistry.", "reasoning": "Fe0 (metallic iron) is established as a potent prebiotic reductant capable of reducing \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids via reductive amination (Wang et al., 2011; Barge et al., 2019; Sources 1026). The selective reduction of one carbonyl in a dicarbonyl compound on heterogeneous metal surfaces is documented in modern catalysis. Under prebiotic conditions, Fe0 was abundant from meteoritic iron and would have been present in surface environments near hydrothermal outflows. The ketone-selective reduction is plausible based on preferential surface binding of the less sterically hindered keto group."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis of lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "FTT synthesis producing C3 oxygenated products including hydroxy-aldehydes"}, "mechanism": "CO and H2 undergo Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis on magnetite surfaces, producing a product distribution that includes C3 oxygenated compounds. Lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal, CH3CH(OH)CHO) forms through chain growth from C1 surface intermediates: formyl \u2192 C2 aldehyde \u2192 hydroxylation and extension to give the C3 hydroxy-aldehyde. Oxygen incorporation during chain growth yields the 2-hydroxy substitution pattern.", "reasoning": "FTT synthesis on magnetite produces a range of oxygenated organic products including alcohols, aldehydes, and hydroxy-compounds up to C4 and beyond (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). Hydroxy-aldehydes are among the observed product types. While lactaldehyde specifically has not been isolated from FTT experiments, the product distribution from FTT includes C3 oxygenated species, and hydroxy-aldehyde formation is thermodynamically and mechanistically consistent with the FTT chain-growth mechanism (Sources 19309, 19315). This provides a direct hydrothermal route to lactaldehyde bypassing the formose pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + HCN + NH3 to threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral to mildly alkaline pH (7-9), evaporitic pool environment"}, "mechanism": "The Strecker synthesis proceeds in two steps: (1) lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO) reacts with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base, CH3CH(OH)CH=NH) with loss of H2O; (2) HCN adds to the electrophilic imine carbon (nucleophilic addition) to form the \u03b1-aminonitrile product, 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (CH3CH(OH)CH(NH2)CN). Montmorillonite surfaces concentrate reactants and catalyze imine formation through acid-base catalysis at clay edge sites.", "reasoning": "The Strecker reaction is universally recognized as the most important prebiotic route to \u03b1-amino acids (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957). Its application to threonine synthesis from lactaldehyde is explicit in the literature as the natural Strecker route to hydroxy-amino acids (Sources 6940, 6942, 985). The reaction requires the aldehyde (lactaldehyde), NH3, and HCN, all of which are prebiotically available. Montmorillonite catalysis of amine-aldehyde condensations is documented (Sources 9431). Short-lived imine intermediates drive the reaction to completion under aqueous conditions (Sources 1026)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly acidic to neutral pH, prolonged aqueous exposure, wet-dry cycling to concentrate"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-CN) of the threonine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to an amide (-CONH2) via nucleophilic addition of water, then to the carboxylic acid (-COOH) with loss of NH3. The overall transformation converts 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid (threonine). The hydrolysis is thermodynamically favorable and occurs spontaneously in aqueous solution over hours to days at ambient temperature.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the well-established second step of the Strecker synthesis. This has been demonstrated under a wide range of prebiotic conditions (Miller, 1957; Wolman et al., 1971; Sources 23270, 6940). The hydrolysis can be acid-catalyzed (pH < 3) or base-catalyzed (pH > 10), but also proceeds at neutral pH over longer timescales. Wet-dry cycling in prebiotic pools can facilitate this process (Sources 512)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Phosphoro-Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + DAP + HCN to N-phosphoro-aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "struvite (MgNH4PO4\u00b76H2O) as phosphate source/surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH 7, evaporitic pool conditions"}, "mechanism": "The phosphoro-Strecker synthesis involves: (1) diamidophosphate (DAP) reacts with the aldehyde group of lactaldehyde to form a phosphoramidate-aldehyde adduct; (2) intramolecular cyclization and HCN addition produce the N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate. DAP acts as both the nitrogen source and a phosphorylating agent, replacing free NH3. This pathway selectively targets aldehydes over ketones, avoiding unnatural disubstituted products.", "reasoning": "The phosphoro-Strecker synthesis was recently demonstrated by Krishnamurthy et al. (2017) and described as a plausible prebiotic pathway that produces N-phosphoroaminonitriles from aldehydes, DAP, and HCN at neutral pH. This pathway is directly relevant to threonine synthesis from lactaldehyde (Sources 21192, 21193). DAP itself has been shown to form under prebiotic conditions from phosphate minerals and ammonia. The selectivity for aldehydes ensures biologically relevant \u03b1-amino acids."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Hydrolysis of N-phosphoro-threonine-aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline pH 13 for N-phosphoramidic acid formation, then neutral hydrolysis; or pH 1.5 for aminonitrile release followed by hydrolysis (Sources 21192)"}, "mechanism": "The N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate can follow multiple hydrolysis routes depending on pH: (1) at pH 13, hydrolysis yields an N-phosphoramidic acid which further hydrolyzes to the amino acid; (2) at pH 1.5, the phosphoryl group is cleaved to release the aminonitrile, which then undergoes standard nitrile hydrolysis to threonine. Both routes converge on threonine as the final product.", "reasoning": "The pH-dependent hydrolysis pathways of phosphoro-Strecker intermediates are detailed by Krishnamurthy et al. (2017), who showed that different products (aminothioamides at pH 7 with H2S, N-phosphoramidic acids at pH 13, aminonitriles at pH 1.5) can all ultimately yield amino acids (Sources 21192, 21193). In a prebiotic pool environment, natural pH fluctuations from volcanic acid rain or mineral dissolution could drive these transformations."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Aldol condensation of glyoxylic acid and acetaldehyde to 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and apatite surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline pH 8-9, evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) enolizes under mildly alkaline conditions to form the nucleophilic enol (CH2=CHOH). This C2 nucleophile attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of glyoxylic acid (OHC-COOH) in an aldol addition, yielding 2-hydroxy-4-oxobutanoic acid initially. Under surface-catalyzed conditions on montmorillonite, keto-enol tautomerization and rearrangement on the clay surface can produce the thermodynamically more stable 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid (the \u03b1-keto acid of threonine). The phosphate mineral surface provides base catalysis for enolization.", "reasoning": "Aldol condensations between \u03b1-keto acids and aldehydes are central to proto-metabolic networks. Springsteen et al. (2018) and Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated that glyoxylate and pyruvate serve as prebiotically relevant starting materials that undergo aldol chemistry to produce C3-C5 metabolic intermediates (Sources 995, 9332, 9334). The specific aldol of glyoxylate + acetaldehyde to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid is a plausible extension of this chemistry, as both substrates are abundantly produced in hydrothermal environments."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Reductive amination of 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid to threonine on metallic iron", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly acidic pH 5-7, surface of meteoritic iron"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-keto acid (3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid, CH3CH(OH)COCOOH) reacts with NH3 at the keto group to form an imine intermediate (CH3CH(OH)C(=NH)COOH). Fe0 acts as a stoichiometric reductant (Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ + 2e-), providing electrons for reduction of the C=N imine bond to give the C-NH2 amine, yielding threonine. The reaction is analogous to biological transamination but uses NH3 directly.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids by metallic iron (Fe0) with NH3 and bifunctional amines has been experimentally demonstrated by Wang et al. (2011, Sources 1026). They showed that Fe0 reduces keto acids (R-CO-COOH) to amino acids in aqueous solution at pH < 7, with imine-like intermediates driving the reaction. This mirrors biological transamination and has been extended to multiple proteinogenic amino acids (Sources 6940, 6944, 6987). The use of Fe0 as reductant is plausible given abundant meteoritic iron on early Earth."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation \u2192 Formose \u2192 Strecker threonine synthesis", "description": "Complete pathway from CO2 through hydrothermal C1 fixation (greigite \u2192 formate \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde), then surface formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde, dehydration to methylglyoxal, reduction to lactaldehyde, and final Strecker synthesis with HCN + NH3 to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation \u2192 Formose \u2192 Phosphoro-Strecker threonine synthesis", "description": "Same upstream as P1 (CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde) but uses the phosphoro-Strecker route with DAP instead of free NH3 for the terminal amino acid synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Direct FTT lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker threonine synthesis", "description": "Fischer-Tropsch-Type synthesis on magnetite directly produces lactaldehyde from CO + H2, bypassing the formose pathway entirely. Lactaldehyde then enters the classical Strecker synthesis with HCN + NH3.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Direct FTT lactaldehyde \u2192 Phosphoro-Strecker threonine synthesis", "description": "FTT synthesis produces lactaldehyde directly, which then undergoes phosphoro-Strecker synthesis with DAP + HCN to yield threonine via N-phosphoroaminonitrile.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid aldol \u2192 Reductive amination", "description": "Pyruvate is synthesized from CO2 hydrothermally, then decarboxylated to acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation with glyoxylic acid to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid, which is reductively aminated on Fe0 surfaces to yield threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid aldol \u2192 Reductive amination", "description": "Acetaldehyde is produced directly via FTT synthesis on magnetite. Combined with hydrothermally-derived glyoxylic acid, the aldol product (threonine's \u03b1-keto acid) is reductively aminated on Fe0 to yield threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "FTT formaldehyde \u2192 Formose glycolaldehyde \u2192 Full formose-Strecker", "description": "Hydrothermal FTT provides formaldehyde, which undergoes formose dimerization to glycolaldehyde on borate minerals. Glycolaldehyde extends with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde, which dehydrates to methylglyoxal, is reduced to lactaldehyde, and enters Strecker synthesis. This pathway emphasizes the formose hub of glycolaldehyde.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 Formose methylglyoxal \u2192 Strecker", "description": "Pyruvate from hydrothermal CO2 fixation is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde. Independently, formaldehyde from FTT undergoes formose to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde. Glyceraldehyde dehydrates to methylglyoxal, which is reduced to lactaldehyde on Fe0. Lactaldehyde enters Strecker synthesis. This pathway shows how pyruvate connects to the acetaldehyde hub, though the terminal steps proceed through the formose-derived intermediates.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Complete FTT \u2192 Direct lactaldehyde \u2192 Reductive amination bypass", "description": "FTT produces both lactaldehyde (C3 hydroxy-aldehyde) and acetaldehyde on magnetite. Glyoxylic acid from mackinawite combines with acetaldehyde in an aldol to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid, which is reductively aminated. Simultaneously, FTT lactaldehyde provides a parallel Strecker route. Both converge on threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Pyruvate \u2192 Acetaldehyde + Glyoxylate \u2192 \u03b1-Keto acid \u2192 Reductive amination (pure metabolic analog)", "description": "This pathway most closely mirrors biological threonine biosynthesis analogs via proto-metabolic chemistry. Pyruvate and glyoxylic acid are both produced from CO2 on iron-sulfur minerals. Pyruvate is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, which undergoes aldol with glyoxylate to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid. Reductive amination on Fe0 with NH3 produces threonine, mimicking biological transamination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_004", "mol_007"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Formaldehyde - key C1 building block produced hydrothermally, consumed in formose chemistry", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "Acetaldehyde - C2 hub produced by two independent routes (pyruvate decarboxylation and FTT), feeds into \u03b1-keto acid aldol chemistry", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_017"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Lactaldehyde - critical C3 aldehyde hub where formose and FTT pathways converge; feeds directly into both Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker terminal syntheses", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_013", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_004", "description": "Hydrogen cyanide - essential C1+N building block consumed in both Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker routes", "incoming_reactions": [], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_013", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Carbon monoxide - C1 intermediate produced from formate dehydration, consumed in all three FTT syntheses (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_012"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 541629.7600269318, "success": true, "error_message": null}
