iption implies acetaldehyde feeds into the formose methylglyoxal route, but the actual reaction network shows methylglyoxal arising from glyceraldehyde dehydration (rxn_010), not from acetaldehyde. This creates a coherence gap.', \"This pathway is described as 'Complete FTT \u2192 Direct lactaldehyde \u2192 Reductive amination bypass' but is incoherent. The reductive amination reaction (rxn_018) requires mol_020 (3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid), not lactaldehyde. There is no reaction in the network converting lactaldehyde to the keto acid required for reductive amination. The pathway as described cannot reach the target through the stated mechanism.\", \"Labeled as 'pure metabolic analog,' this pathway closely mirrors P5 using pyruvate and glyoxylate as starting points. The biological analogy is compelling\u2014this resembles the extant biosynthetic logic. The glyoxylic acid formation (rxn_007) remains the weakest step. The aldol condensation to the \u03b1-keto acid and subsequent reductive amination are well-supported by literature on Fe\u2070-catalyzed amino acid synthesis.\"]\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid) is synthesized through a convergent prebiotic network with three major classes of terminal chemistry: (1) classical Strecker synthesis on lactaldehyde, (2) phosphoro-Strecker synthesis on lactaldehyde with DAP, and (3) reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid on metallic iron. The key C3 aldehyde lactaldehyde is produced via formose chemistry (formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde), while the \u03b1-keto acid is produced via cyanide-catalyzed acyloin condensation of glyoxylate with acetaldehyde. Upstream C1-C2 building blocks originate from hydrothermal CO2 reduction and Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on iron-sulfur minerals. Acetaldehyde serves as a major hub, produced via both FTT synthesis and pyruvate decarboxylation. Glyoxylate is produced via both direct CO2 reduction and UV-driven oxidation of glycolaldehyde, providing convergent routes to the metabolic pathway. The network spans all three environments: Hydrothermal (CO2 fixation, FTT), Surface (formose, Strecker, acyloin), and Biochemical (hydrolysis, assembly).\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methylglyoxal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h3H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2-3,4H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(6)4(7)8/h2,5H,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-2(7)3(5)4-6/h2-3,7H,5H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"H4NO2P(NH2)2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"diamidophosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAP\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9N3O3P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"N-phosphoro-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-phosphoro-threonine-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2OS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanethioamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminothioamide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-amino-3-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h3H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on the greigite [Fe4S4]-analog surface where it undergoes two-electron reduction by H2 via surface hydride intermediates to yield formate (HCOO-). The mineral surface stabilizes the transition state and lowers the activation barrier for C-H bond formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is one of the best-established prebiotic carbon fixation steps. Greigite is a structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters and has been experimentally shown to reduce CO2 under hydrothermal conditions (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). This reaction mimics the first step of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate decomposition to CO on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"higher temperature zone of vent system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate decomposes on magnetite surfaces via dehydration, losing H2O to yield CO. At elevated temperatures (>400K), this thermal decomposition is thermodynamically favored. Magnetite surface Lewis acid sites activate the formate C-O bond.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decomposition of formate to CO is well-established in hydrothermal chemistry. Magnetite catalyzes this process at moderate hydrothermal temperatures (He et al., 2010). CO is a critical feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis and is produced in vent systems through multiple routes including the reverse water-gas shift reaction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"FTT conditions, CO:H2 ratio ~1:1\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs dissociatively on magnetite surfaces. Hydrogenation of surface carbide/oxycarbide intermediates produces formaldehyde (H2CO) as the simplest oxygenated C1 product. Formaldehyde is released into solution where it is partially stabilized by hydration to methylene glycol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces oxygenated C1-C3 products including formaldehyde. Magnetite has been shown to catalyze FTT reactions at relatively low temperatures (~360K and above), with carbonaceous chondrite magnetite also demonstrating this activity (McCollom et al., 1999; Bernstein et al., 2006; Source 19309, 19315). Formaldehyde is a foundational prebiotic feedstock molecule (Wolman et al., 1971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"FTT conditions, longer chain growth than formaldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO hydrogenation on magnetite proceeds via chain growth to C2 oxygenates. Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) forms through insertion of CO into surface methyl intermediates followed by hydrogenation and desorption. The C2 aldehyde is a common FTT product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT synthesis on magnetite and related iron oxides produces C2 oxygenates including acetaldehyde with well-documented yields (McCollom et al., 1999; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001). Acetaldehyde is a more plausible FTT product than C3 oxygenates due to the decreasing yield with chain length (Schulz-Flory distribution).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite-magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite + magnetite mixed phase\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions, pH 9-11, multi-step reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction on mixed iron-sulfur/oxide mineral phases yields pyruvate through intermediate C1 and C2 species. The reaction proceeds via formate \u2192 acetate/acetyl intermediate \u2192 pyruvate, catalyzed by the mixed mineral surface which provides both reducing power and C-C coupling capability.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated that CO2 can be reduced to pyruvate and other TCA cycle intermediates under simulated alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions using native iron minerals. This represents a key result supporting the iron-sulfur world hypothesis and the emergence of proto-metabolic carbon fixation. Yields are low but the reaction is thermodynamically feasible under vent conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, thermal\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal non-oxidative decarboxylation at C1, losing CO2 to form acetaldehyde. The pyrite surface facilitates this by stabilizing the carbanion/enol intermediate. The reaction: CH3COCOOH \u2192 CH3CHO + CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids is well-established in hydrothermal chemistry. Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde occurs readily at temperatures above 350K (Cody et al., 2004). This creates a convergent route to acetaldehyde from pyruvate, complementing FTT synthesis and providing environmental redundancy.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to glyoxylate on mackinawite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH, H2-rich, requires C-C coupling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is reduced on mackinawite surfaces through sequential hydrogenation to formaldehyde, followed by CO2 carboxylation of the C1 intermediate to yield the C2 \u03b1-keto acid glyoxylate (OHC-COOH). FeS provides both the reducing equivalents and the catalytic surface for C-C bond formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a central metabolite in protometabolic networks and has been proposed as a prebiotically relevant input (Muchowska et al., 2019, 2020; Source 995, 9332, 9334). Its formation from CO2 on FeS surfaces is supported by the broader framework of iron-sulfur world chemistry, though direct experimental yields for glyoxylate specifically are limited. Mackinawite is a precursor to greigite and provides strong reducing power.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose self-condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)2, borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH ~10-11, warm evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo aldol condensation via the Cannizzaro-Butlerov mechanism. The first HCHO molecule is isomerized to a glycolaldehyde enediol intermediate on the mineral surface, which then attacks a second HCHO molecule. Borate minerals stabilize the sugar products and prevent runaway polymerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction (Butlerov, 1861) is the classical prebiotic route to sugars from formaldehyde. The formation of glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde self-condensation is the initiating step, catalyzed by calcium hydroxide or alkaline mineral surfaces. Borate minerals stabilize the intermediates (Ricardo et al., 2004). This reaction is prebiotically plausible in evaporitic surface pools. Source 6942 notes formaldehyde as a robust prebiotic source molecule.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose aldol: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde enolizes under alkaline conditions and its enediol attacks formaldehyde in an aldol addition. The product glyceraldehyde is stabilized by borate complexation, preventing further aldol reactions and isomerization to dihydroxyacetone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde step is a well-established formose reaction intermediate. Borate stabilization of glyceraldehyde has been demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004) and Kim et al. (2011). This is critical because without borate, glyceraldehyde rapidly isomerizes or degrades. Source 16400 highlights the stabilization of aldehydes in prebiotic chemical networks.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Dehydration of glyceraldehyde to methylglyoxal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (acid clay surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"dry phase of wet-dry cycle, mild heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes acid-catalyzed dehydration on montmorillonite clay surfaces during the drying phase of wet-dry cycles. Loss of water from the C2 hydroxyl yields the \u03b1,\u03b2-dicarbonyl methylglyoxal (CH3-CO-CHO). The clay's Br\u00f8nsted acid sites catalyze the elimination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dehydration of trioses to methylglyoxal is a well-known reaction in sugar chemistry. Under mildly acidic, heated conditions on clay surfaces, glyceraldehyde readily loses water to form methylglyoxal (Thornalley, 2008). Wet-dry cycling on mineral surfaces drives dehydration reactions essential for prebiotic chemistry (Source 512). Montmorillonite's acidic interlayer provides the catalytic environment.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on FeS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS) surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH, FeS as both catalyst and reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Methylglyoxal (CH3-CO-CHO) is selectively reduced at the ketone (C2) position on the FeS surface. In aqueous solution, the aldehyde group is predominantly hydrated as a geminal diol (>95% hydrated at 25\u00b0C for small aldehydes), protecting it from reduction. The exposed keto group is reduced by surface-bound hydrides on mackinawite, yielding lactaldehyde (CH3-CHOH-CHO). FeS provides electrons: FeS + 2H+ \u2192 Fe2+ + H2S, generating reducing equivalents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FeS/mackinawite-mediated reductions of carbonyl compounds have been demonstrated by Heinen & Lauwers (1996) and Cody et al. (2004). The selectivity for keto over aldehyde reduction is justified by the preferential aqueous hydration of aldehydes (geminal diol formation, Khydration >> 1 for simple aldehydes) which protects the aldehyde while leaving the less-hydrated ketone exposed for surface reduction. This is consistent with known reactivity patterns in aqueous organic chemistry (Aston & Greenburg, 1940). The reaction occurs at the hydrothermal-surface interface where methylglyoxal from surface formose chemistry encounters reducing FeS minerals.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + NH3 + HCN to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH 6-8, concentrated evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde (CH3-CHOH-CHO) condenses with NH3 to form an imine intermediate (CH3-CHOH-CH=NH) via nucleophilic addition-elimination. The imine then undergoes nucleophilic addition by HCN (CN-) at the electrophilic imine carbon to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile: CH3-CHOH-CH(NH2)-CN (threonine aminonitrile). Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and stabilizes the imine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker reaction is the most extensively studied prebiotic amino acid synthesis pathway (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957). For threonine, lactaldehyde serves as the appropriate aldehyde precursor. The reaction proceeds efficiently at ambient temperatures in aqueous solution at near-neutral pH (Sources 6940, 6942, 985, 15634). Montmorillonite clay enhances the reaction by adsorbing and concentrating the reactants (Source 9431). Wolman et al. (1971) demonstrated amino acid synthesis from aldehydes and ammonia under simulated prebiotic conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, extended time at warm temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-CN) of threonine aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (-CONH2) via nucleophilic addition of water, then to the carboxylic acid (-COOH) with release of ammonia. Overall: R-CH(NH2)-CN + 2H2O \u2192 R-CH(NH2)-COOH + NH3. The amino group remains intact throughout.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid is the terminal step of the Strecker synthesis. Under mildly acidic or neutral aqueous conditions, aminonitriles hydrolyze over timescales of days to weeks at prebiotic temperatures (Miller, 1957; Source 6940). This step is thermodynamically favorable and does not require a catalyst, though warm acidic conditions accelerate it. The reaction represents the transition from Surface/prebiotic chemistry to a Biochemical product.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + DAP + HCN to N-phosphoro-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7, ambient temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with diamidophosphate (DAP) at neutral pH to form an N-phosphoroimine intermediate. This activated imine then reacts with HCN to form the N-phosphoroaminonitrile. The phosphoryl group activates the imine toward CN- attack and protects the amino group, controlling selectivity. The reaction selectively targets aldehydes over ketones.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Krishnamurthy et al. (2017, Sources 21192, 21193) demonstrated the phosphoro-Strecker synthesis as a prebiotically plausible route to amino acids. The pathway starts with aldehyde + DAP + HCN at pH 7 to form N-phosphoroaminonitriles. This modification of the Strecker reaction is significant because it provides regioselectivity (aldehydes over ketones, avoiding \u03b1,\u03b1-disubstituted amino acids) and connects amino acid synthesis to phosphorus chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of N-phosphoro-aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 13 initially (for dephosphorylation), then neutral for nitrile hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under alkaline conditions (pH 13), the N-phosphoryl group is hydrolyzed to release phosphate and yield the free aminonitrile. The nitrile group then undergoes hydrolysis to the amide and subsequently to the carboxylic acid under mildly acidic conditions, yielding threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Krishnamurthy et al. (2017, Sources 21192, 21193) showed that N-phosphoroaminonitriles can be converted to amino acids through pH-dependent hydrolysis steps. At pH 13, N-phosphoramidic acids form; under more acidic conditions, the aminonitrile is released and hydrolyzed to the amino acid. The pH cycling required is prebiotically plausible in environments with pH gradients such as alkaline vent-ocean interfaces.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanide-catalyzed acyloin condensation of glyoxylate with acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, HCN as catalytic umpolung agent\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH, HCN present in catalytic amounts, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide ion (CN-) attacks the aldehyde carbon of glyoxylate to form a cyanohydrin (HO-CH(CN)-COOH). The cyanohydrin undergoes tautomerization to an acyl anion equivalent (umpolung), which then attacks the electrophilic carbonyl of acetaldehyde. The resulting adduct eliminates HCN to yield 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid (CH3-CH(OH)-CO-COOH). This is a benzoin-type condensation catalyzed by cyanide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanide-catalyzed acyloin (benzoin) condensations are well-established in organic chemistry (Lapworth, 1903) and are prebiotically plausible given the expected abundance of HCN on early Earth (Source 15634). This umpolung mechanism converts an aldehyde into a nucleophilic acyl equivalent, enabling C-C bond formation between glyoxylate and acetaldehyde. Glyoxylate and pyruvate are considered prebiotically relevant protometabolic inputs (Muchowska et al., 2019, 2020; Sources 995, 9332). The montmorillonite surface concentrates the reactants.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid to threonine on Fe0\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"metallic iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH < 7, NH3 or NH2OH as nitrogen source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-keto group of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid condenses with ammonia to form an imine intermediate (Schiff base). Metallic iron (Fe0) provides reducing equivalents (Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ + 2e-) that reduce the imine to the amine, yielding threonine. The reaction proceeds through a short-lived imine-like intermediate under aqueous conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Barge et al. (2019) demonstrated that metallic iron (Fe0) can drive reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids under mild aqueous conditions at pH < 7 (Source 1026). This non-enzymatic pathway mirrors biological transamination and connects \u03b1-keto acid intermediates of protometabolism to amino acid synthesis. The reaction uses ammonia or bifunctional amines (NH2XH, X=O or NH) as nitrogen sources. Fe0 is a plausible prebiotic reductant in hydrothermal systems.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photocatalytic oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 anatase photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (~200-320 nm, no ozone layer), shallow surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV light excites TiO2 to generate electron-hole pairs. The photogenerated holes oxidize glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) at the primary alcohol position: HOCH2CHO \u2192 OHC-CHO (glyoxal) \u2192 OHC-COOH (glyoxylic acid) via sequential two-electron oxidations. The TiO2 surface provides both the photocatalytic activity and adsorption sites for the substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO2 (anatase) is an established UV photocatalyst for prebiotic organic transformations on early Earth where strong UV radiation reached the surface due to the absence of an ozone layer (Source 21187). Photocatalytic oxidation of alcohols to aldehydes and acids is well-documented on TiO2 surfaces. This reaction provides an alternative surface-environment route to glyoxylate, complementing the hydrothermal CO2 reduction pathway (rxn_007) and creating convergence at the glyoxylate node.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile thiolysis to aminothioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"stibnite (sulfide mineral surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7, H2S-rich surface waters\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogen sulfide (H2S) attacks the nitrile carbon of threonine aminonitrile in a nucleophilic addition. The sulfur atom of H2S adds across the C\u2261N triple bond, yielding the thioamide (-C(=S)NH2). The stibnite surface provides a sulfide-rich microenvironment and activates the nitrile toward nucleophilic attack.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The cyanosulfidic pathway (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017; Sources 9381, 9382) highlights the role of H2S in prebiotic synthesis. Krishnamurthy et al. (Sources 21192, 21193) showed that N-phosphoroaminonitriles can be converted to aminothioamides by reaction with H2S at pH 7. The thiolysis of nitriles to thioamides is also part of the broader Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic framework. Stibnite provides the sulfide-rich catalytic surface.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of aminothioamide to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic conditions, extended aqueous contact\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The thioamide group (-C(=S)NH2) of threonine aminothioamide undergoes hydrolysis in aqueous solution. Water attacks the thioamide carbon, displacing H2S, forming first the amide and then the carboxylic acid: R-C(=S)NH2 + H2O \u2192 R-C(=O)NH2 + H2S \u2192 R-COOH + NH3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thioamide hydrolysis to carboxylic acids proceeds under mild aqueous conditions and is a key step in the cyanosulfidic pathway to amino acids (Patel et al., 2015; Krishnamurthy et al., 2017; Sources 21192, 21193). This terminal step converts the cyanosulfidic intermediate to the final amino acid product.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis on methylglyoxal to 2-amino-3-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\":", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 666445.3949928284, "success": false, "error_message": "Expecting value: line 560 column 16 (char 32794)"}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T23:04:54.794837", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\