orm threonine's \u03b1-keto acid, then reductive amination yields threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_006", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_021", "mol_010", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "FTT CO \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate-independent Strecker via formose convergence", "description": "CO from RWGS feeds FTT synthesis of acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde combines with glyoxylic acid to form \u03b1-keto acid. Simultaneously, CO2\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde enters formose. Both routes converge: formose provides the glyceraldehyde\u2192methylglyoxal\u2192lactaldehyde for Strecker, while acetaldehyde feeds the \u03b1-keto acid route as parallel backup.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Cyanosulfidic \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 formose \u2192 Strecker to threonine", "description": "Formaldehyde and HCN form glycolonitrile via cyanosulfidic chemistry. UV-driven processing converts glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde. Glycolaldehyde then enters the formose sequence to glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 acetol \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_023", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Cyanosulfidic \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 formose \u2192 Phosphoro-Strecker to threonine", "description": "Same cyanosulfidic upstream as P6 but diverges at lactaldehyde to use the phosphoro-Strecker pathway with DAP and HCN.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_023", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Mixed hydrothermal: pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde + FTT formaldehyde \u2192 formose-Strecker", "description": "Pyruvate from CO2 fixation decarboxylates to acetaldehyde (hydrothermal). Formaldehyde from formate reduction enters formose on surface. Formose produces glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 acetol \u2192 lactaldehyde. Lactaldehyde undergoes Strecker synthesis to threonine. Acetaldehyde from pyruvate and formaldehyde from formate both originate hydrothermally but follow different reduction pathways.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_021", "mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Dual convergence: FTT formaldehyde + FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 parallel keto-acid and Strecker routes", "description": "RWGS produces CO, which feeds FTT synthesis of both acetaldehyde and (via formate) formaldehyde. Formaldehyde enters formose \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 threonine. Acetaldehyde feeds the acyloin route with glyoxylic acid \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid \u2192 reductive amination \u2192 threonine. Both routes produce threonine independently.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Glyoxylic acid + pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-keto acid \u2192 phosphoro-Strecker hybrid", "description": "Glyoxylic acid and acetaldehyde (from pyruvate decarboxylation) undergo acyloin condensation to form 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid. This \u03b1-keto acid is then reductively aminated on Fe0 to yield threonine. This pathway represents a purely metabolic analog route through \u03b1-keto acid intermediates, paralleling the transamination logic of modern biochemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_006", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_021", "mol_010", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_019"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_009", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_019"], "description": "Formaldehyde is the primary C1 hub. Produced by formate reduction (rxn_002) in hydrothermal vents. Consumed by formose self-condensation (rxn_008), formose chain extension to glyceraldehyde (rxn_009), and cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile formation (rxn_019). It connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to all downstream surface chemistry."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_017"], "description": "Acetaldehyde is produced by two independent hydrothermal routes: FTT synthesis from CO (rxn_004) and pyruvate decarboxylation (rxn_007). This creates genuine convergence from different carbon fixation mechanisms. Acetaldehyde is consumed in the cyanide-catalyzed acyloin condensation with glyoxylic acid (rxn_017) to form threonine's \u03b1-keto acid."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011"], "description": "Methylglyoxal is the critical C3 intermediate formed from glyceraldehyde dehydration (rxn_010). It serves as the gateway between formose sugar chemistry and the amino acid Strecker pathway. Reduced to acetol (rxn_011), it connects to lactaldehyde and ultimately threonine."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_013", "rxn_015"], "description": "Lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) is the key aldehyde substrate for both Strecker (rxn_013) and phosphoro-Strecker (rxn_015) routes to threonine. Produced via acetol tautomerization (rxn_012). All formose-based pathways converge here before diverging into the two Strecker variants."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_019", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_017"], "description": "Glyoxylic acid is the simplest \u03b1-keto acid, produced from CO2 reduction on mackinawite (rxn_006). It serves as the electrophilic partner in the cyanide-catalyzed acyloin condensation with acetaldehyde (rxn_017), providing the carboxyl terminus of threonine's \u03b1-keto acid precursor."}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 610916.6378974915, "success": true, "error_message": null}
